<HEADLINE> Scientists Say Adult Brains Can Grow New Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from United
States and Sweden have found for the first time that adults
could grow new neurons or brain cells even at 60s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
This finding may bring a distant hope for treating brain
diseases or damages.
</P>
<P>
Reporting in the latest issue of Nature Medicine, researchers
from the Salk Institute for Biological Studies in U.S. Califonia
and the Sahlgrenska University Hospital in Goteborg, Sweden,
said the new neurons that form circuits were found in just one
small part of the brain--the hippocampus, a deep-brain structure
that is important for learning and memory.
</P>
<P>
They examined autopsy specimens from 5 people who had been
given a drug called BrdU because of cancer in their mouths or
throats. The drug is taken by dividing cells. Doctors had
administered it to see how rapidly the patients' tumors were
growing.
</P>
<P>
They reasoned that if cells in the brain were dividing to grow
new cells, they would take up the drug.
</P>
<P>
Eventually they found the drug in hippocampus of all the 5 people.
Among the 5 people, two were at the age of 50s, two at 60s and
one at 72. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
