<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quebec's Liberals Facing Uphill Battle in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Quebec's Liberal Party still has
a chance to win, even though the ruling Parti Quebecois (PQ) holds
the upper hand going into next month's election in the
French-speaking province of Canada, the lastest poll shows.
</P>
<P>
The survey, published Friday by the newspaper Gazette, pegs the
Liberal Party's popular support as of this week at 46.5 percent,
compared with 44.7 percent for the PQ.
</P>
<P>
The Action Democratique got 6.6 percent and the Equality Party
less than one percent. The remaining 1.4 percent was spread among
fringe parties.
</P>
<P>
But because of the uneven distribution of Liberal and PQ
support, such a count in practice would have produced another PQ
majority government had the election been held this week, said
Gilles Therrien, president of SOM polling firm that conducted the
survey.
</P>
<P>
The key PQ advantage is its significant lead among francophone
voters, who support the PQ by 53 percent to 38 percent for the
Liberals.
</P>
<P>
The Liberals are the overwhelming choice of the non-francophone
electorate, by 84 percent to 9.6 percent for the PQ, according to
the survey.
</P>
<P>
Quebec voters also have far more confidence in PQ leader Lucien
Bouchard as premier than in Liberal leader Jean Charest.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-nine percent were very or somewhat satisfied with
Bouchard's performance as premier, while 43 percent were generally
satisfied with Charest's performance in province politics.
</P>
<P>
The survey was compiled from interviews conducted from October
23 to 27, the day before the election was called, with a sample of
1,22 eligible voters across the province. It has a margin of error
of 3.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
