<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Homes Sales Decline in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. new home sales fell
1 percent to a nine-month low in September, the third consecutive
drop after reaching the record high in June, the Commerce
Department said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
New single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 822,000, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
It was the longest declines since early 1995 and left the
inventory of unsold homes at 292,000, the highest level in 19
months.
</P>
<P>
The September decline was sharpest in the Midwest, 12.9 percent
to a rate of 175,000. Sales fell 5.5 percent in the West to
224,000, 3.3 percent in the South to 353,000 and 2.7 percent to
71,000 in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, sales had surged to a record 919,000 rate in June,
the highest on record since the department began tracking sales in
1963. The buying heat was attributed mainly to low mortgage rates
combined with strong job growth.
</P>
<P>
However, in recent months, the stock market's problems have
spooked some buyers, and economic and job growth has slowed
somewhat in response to Asia's economic slump.
</P>
<P>
The median price of a new home in September was 152,000 U.S.
dollars, up 3.9 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
