<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economic Growth Rebounds in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. economic growth moved
forward at a 3.3 percent seasonally adjusted annual rate in the
third quarter, the Commerce Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the world financial chaos, the economy grew at a
subdued 1.8 percent rate in the second quarter period after
soaring at a 5.5 percent rate during the first three months of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Exports fell at a 2.9 percent rate, the third consecutive
quarter of decline, while imports rose at a 3.4 percent rate. The
resulting deterioration in the trade deficit knocked nearly a
percentage point from the overall growth rate.
</P>
<P>
However, that wasn't as bad as the previous two quarters, when
the ballooning trade deficit reduced growth by more than two
percentage points in each.
</P>
<P>
Businesses turned cautious in the third quarter. Though
investment in new computers remained strong, overall spending on
new equipment increased at a 1.1 percent annual rate, the smallest
gain in nearly seven years. Spending on new buildings and
structures fell at a 6.5 percent rate, the worst showing in some 4
years.
</P>
<P>
Growth in housing construction dipped from a robust 15.3
percent in the first half of the year to a still-substantial 6.8
percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending, which represents about two-thirds of
economic activity, grew at a healthy 3.9 percent annual rate in
the third quarter, after shooting up at a 6.1 percent rate during
the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Third-quarter growth was heavily influenced by a shift in
inventory growth and by the General Motors strikes, which began in
June. Without a sharp slowdown in inventory accumulation in the
second quarter and a rebound in the third, the economy would have
grown at a 4.6 percent pace in the second and a 2.3 percent rate
in the third.
</P>
<P>
Auto production fell in both quarters. And, a decline in auto
sales in the third completely offset increased consumer spending
on other big-ticket durable goods. Thus, all the third-quarter
growth in consumer spending came in services and non-durable goods
such as food, fuel and clothing.
</P>
<P>
Government spending, meanwhile, grew at a 1.4 percent rate in
the third quarter, down from 3.7 percent in the second.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide inflation hit a 35-year low. Prices rose at an
0.8 percent annual rate. The various changes left the economy
producing goods and services in the third quarter at a 8.53
trillion U.S. dollar annual rate, unadjusted for inflation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
