<HEADLINE> Canada's Economy Rebounds in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Canada's economy rebounded in
August after four months of decline, Statistics Canada said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) increased by 0.7 percent,
bringing the value of economic activity back to its previous peak
early this year.
</P>
<P>
"The primary factor underlying the correction was the recovery
from the effects of strikes in June and July," the statistics
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output rose 2.8 percent following four months of
declines, with increases recorded in 16 of 22 groups.
</P>
<P>
Production of motor vehicles rose 24.4 percent, and production
of motor vehicle parts shot up 26.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Construction activity rebounded somewhat in the wake of strikes
in southern Ontario province, but the level of output is only back
to June levels, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Housing starts were up sharply in August, following four
consecutive months of decline.
</P>
<P>
In August, wholesaling activities declined by 0.3 percent,
further extending the period of lacklustre growth. Weakness was
widespread in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Retail trade sales slipped 0.2 percent, with supermarkets,
department and other stores reporting lower sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
