<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Tightens Financial Market Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 30 ( Xinhua) -- India tightened operational
norms Friday for the financial market to insulate it from currency
crisis like those in East Asia while underplaying the inflationary
pressures by leaving "high money supply" in the economy untouched
in its busy season credit policy.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Bank of India (RBI), the central bank of the country,
announced that Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) would be raised from
the present eight percent to nine percent with effect from the
next financial year and brought income recognition in provisioning
norms for government guaranteed advances on par with other such
advances from the fiscal year 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from Mumbai, India's
financial city 1400 kilometers southwest of here, that RBI had
also introduced provisioning requirement for standard assets
effective from the financial year ending March 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Carrying forward the financial sector reforms through a phased
implementation of stricter provisioning norms for banks and
financial institutions as well as government securities to provide
for additional risk coverage, RBI left lending rates and cash
reserve ratio unchanged at nine and 11 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
PTI quoted RBI Governor Bimal Jalan as cautioning that it would
adopt tighter monetary stances if the inflation increases further
or in case of external pressures.
</P>
<P>
In his mid-year review of the monetary credit policy for
1998-99, Jalan said RBI had deliberately avoided monetary and
credit policy decisions in its review to make the event devoid of
any hype.
</P>
<P>
The Southeast Asian crisis had clearly influenced the
formulation of the busy season (October-March) credit policy by
the Indian central bank which sought to move towards full
disclosures and transparency in banking operations in line with
global practices.
</P>
<P>
Jalan expressed concern over the eight percent inflation rate,
saying that money supply growth was much higher than expected
growth of the economy and was inconsistent with the objective of
general price stability maintenance though the outlook for
industrial growth continued to be uncertain and external
environment was highly unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
The RBI governor advised banks to introduce effective risk
management systems to cover credit risk, market risk and
operational risk on a priority basis.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive risk measurement approach should be adopted and
detailed structure of operating limits, guidelines and other
parameters should be put in place, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
