<HEADLINE> UK House Prices Will Beat Inflation, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- House prices in Britain will
continue to rise by more than inflation for several years,
according to report by investment bank Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
The report says the house prices compared with disposable
incomes look "pretty low", and as a proportion of total private
sector wealth, the value of residential property is lower than at
any time in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch adds that worries that slowing population growth
and the increased burden of the welfare state will have a negative
effect on the housing market.
</P>
<P>
It expects house prices to rise by more than consumer price
inflation for the next few years, but by 2004 it expects prices to
cool off and there will be zero movement in house prices for a
couple of years.
</P>
<P>
But in the longer term, the report expects rises in house
prices of about 2 percent in real terms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
