<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Chief Judge Presents Report on Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 30 (Xinhua) -- About 1,200 people involved in
636 prosecution cases were tried by courts in Vietnam in the first
nine months of this year, Vietnam News Agency Friday quoted an
official report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report was delivered by Chief Judge of the People's Supreme
Court Trinh Hong Duong at the National Assembly on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The tried people included 720 in 360 cases of corruption, 133
people in 57 smuggling cases, and 342 people in 219 cases of
prohibited commodities trading.
</P>
<P>
The chief judge also reported that there were a number of
prosecutions for drug trafficking, prostitution and child rapes.
</P>
<P>
Local people's courts settled over 66,000 or 82.29 percent of
the total l80,300 civil disputes heard by them.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 48 percent of the civil disputes were settled through
negotiation. Through reconciliation, the courts assisted 8 percent
of the troubled families and marriages to result in reunification,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
The chief judge admitted that there remains weaknesses and
shortcomings in the operation of their respective sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
