<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Has 800,000 Internet Users </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Africa has the lowest Internet
usage in the world, accounting for only 800,000 or 0.54 percent
of the global Internet user population of about 150 million, a
Nigerian communications official has said.
</P>
<P>
Ogbonnaya Iromantu, Executive Vice-Chairman of the Nigerian
Communications Commission (NCC), said out of the figure, about
700,000 Internet users are in South Africa, 10,000 in Zimbabwe
and 7,000 in Ghana and Nigeria, The Guardian newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, he said, the United States has about 79 million
Internet users and Europe 34 million while Asia and Pacific have
24 million.
</P>
<P>
The NCC boss said the inadequate general level of
telecommunications facilities was clearly the most critical
inhibiting element to electronic information sharing in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said at the on-going Second International Conference on
Broadcasting in Africa held in Nigerian capital Abuja that Africa
spends about three billion U.S. Dollars to import
telecommunications equipment and some 600 million Dollars to
connect one African country to the other through European
countries every year.
</P>
<P>
This amount of money, he noted, is enough for some countries
to maintain sustainable development of their telecommunications
infrastructure and to develop local manufacturing competence in
the continent.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian official said the way to redress the situation
included support for technical training and skills as well as
development of access points and demand in secondary cities and
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The journey to full Internet connectivity in Nigeria has been
tortuous due to the different perceptions of the technology, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
