<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Rebel Leader Presses for Immediate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting rebel leader
Ernest Wamba dia Wamba of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
Friday pressed for face-to-face talks with DRC President Laurent
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Pretoria, the administrative
capital of South Africa, Wamba dia Wamba warned that war in the
DRC could spread to the rest of Africa if peace negotiations were
not started immediately.
</P>
<P>
Wamba dia Wamba said Kabila should be responsible for
involving other countries in the war. "Peace will only be
possible when Kabila starts negotiation himself."
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader said he told South African President Nelson
Mandela Thursday that he would opt for a ceasefire as long as
Kabila responded positively to peace negotiation.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his forces would not mind if Mandela became
involved in the peace process as long as he could achieve direct
negotiations between the rebels and Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has renewed its effort for peace
settlement of the DRC conflict, which started in early August.
</P>
<P>
Following his talks with Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and
Rwandan Vice President Paul Kagame last week, Mandela also
exchanged views with Namibian President Sam Nujoma over the DRC
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, together with Zimbabwe, Angola and Chad, have
deployed thousands of troops in the DRC to help Kabila's
government quell rebels. Meanwhile, Uganda and Rwanda have been
accused by the DRC government of supporting rebels in vast
central African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
