<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: ANC's Row With Truth Body Backfires (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After the dismissal of the ANC's court bid, ANC president and
state Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said the party would decide
whether to appeal after analyzing the reasoning behind the
ruling. The judge did not give the reasons Thursday due to
limited time.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who succeeded Nelson Mandela as ANC leader late last
year, said the TRC's findings against the party were "wrong and
misguided".
</P>
<P>
The ANC's botched court bid also revealed a division within
the party. Some party officials said the decision to take the
TRC issue to court appeared to have been the decision of a small
leadership group, and some of the ANC's top officials had been
left in the dark about the plan.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's spokesman said Thursday that the state president had
not been consulted on the court move beforehand. While receiving
the report from Tutu, Mandela said he accepted the report with
all its imperfections, as an aid to help the people of the
country to reconcile and build the nation.
</P>
<P>
Two party officials who had been most closely involved in TRC
issues -- Justice Minister Dullah Omar and Premier Mathews Phosa
of Mpumalanga Province, were reportedly only notified of the
decision to take court action. Their opinion on the matter was
not sought. Both men participated on behalf of the ANC in
drafting the law setting up the TRC.
</P>
<P>
Some ANC parliament members said the court bid to suppress
criticism was a mistake, which could damage ANC's reputation at
home and abroad for fair-mindedness and a willingness to face up
to the past.
</P>
<P>
The ANC's wrangle with the TRC seems not yet close to an end.
The party's objection to the TRC findings has given rise to calls
for a general amnesty for apartheid-era human rights violations,
regardless of whether they have satisfied the TRC's requirements
for amnesty.
</P>
<P>
The ANC, which rejected a blanket amnesty in the
constitutional talks, is now caught in a dilemma.
</P>
<P>
After the TRC's amnesty committee has ended its hearings in
four months and all the TRC's work has been completed, the ANC
could see some of its senior members facing lengthy criminal
prosecutions and civil suits for human rights abuses named in the
TRC report.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty committee is yet to deal with the amnesty
applications by 37 ANC leaders, including Mbeki and five cabinet
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties, many of whose members are also threatened
by possible prosecutions, said a general amnesty is needed to
finally close the book on the past, which the TRC process was
intended to bring about.
</P>
<P>
But a blanket amnesty could meet strong opposition from
victims of human rights abuses and from those who want to defend
the TRC process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-30 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Quantity of Contraband Cigarettes Seized in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The Financial Crimes Squad
(SDOE) of Greece's Finance Ministry Friday seized a great quantity
of contraband cigarettes in Piraeus, about 15 kilometers west of
Athens.
</P>
<P>
The SDOE found some two million packets of super king and regal
cigarettes when they checked the four containers, which had been
sent from the United Arab Emirates and arrived in Piraeus earlier
this month, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest single haul of smuggled cigarettes ever
found in Greece.
</P>
<P>
Some 14 million packets of contraband cigarettes have been
confiscated since the beginning of this year in Attica prefecture
alone. 
</P>
