<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: ANC's Row With Truth Body Backfires (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) is counting the cost of a lost
battle against the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC)
which found the party guilty of human rights atrocities during
the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
Some ANC senior officials have voiced their concern that the
failed attempt may tarnish the image of the party.
</P>
<P>
The ANC's last-minute attempt to halt the publication of the
TRC findings failed Thursday after a Cape Town High Court judge
dismissed the party's application for an interdict.
</P>
<P>
Two hours after the ruling, TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu handed
the 3,500-page report to President Nelson Mandela, and
simultaneously it was released to the world through media and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
The report, compiled after 30 months of hearings and
investigations by the commission, found the ANC "morally and
politically responsible for gross human rights abuses" committed
during the anti-apartheid struggle.
</P>
<P>
It held the party accountable for killings of civilians in its
military operations, bombings and assassinations, and for the
injuries and deaths of civilians in its 1985-1987 landmine
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The ANC was also found guilty of killing 76 Inkatha Freedom
Party officials, and torturing and killing its own members in
foreign military camps who were suspected to be informers of the
apartheid state.
</P>
<P>
The TRC in its report blamed the ANC for "creating a climate"
in which supporters believed their illegal actions were
legitimate within the parameters of "people's war" promoted by
the party.
</P>
<P>
Though conceding the ANC's status as part of a legitimate
liberation movement, the commission said "a just war" could not
justify unjust means.
</P>
<P>
The ANC's decision Wednesday evening to apply for an urgent
court interdict to prevent the whole TRC report from being
published caught the whole nation by shock, not least the TRC.
</P>
<P>
The ANC was one of the major proponents of the founding of a
special court to address the injustice during the apartheid
years. It insisted that victims of human rights violations in the
past should be given some kind of recognition and compensation.
</P>
<P>
The TRC was set up in 1995 as a result of a compromise made by
all sides in the multi-party constitutional talks in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Tutu severely criticized the ANC for the legal action. In a
television interview Thursday night, Tutu said the ANC should not
expect special treatment and could not order the TRC to change
findings just because it was the ruling party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
