<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G7 Unveils Action Plan on Global Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven (G7) major
industrialized nations Friday unveiled a package of far-reaching
reforms designed to "strengthen the global financial system".
</P>
<P>
British Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown, whose country
is the current G7 president, said that the measures aim to keep a
tighter check on destabilizing flows of hot money and to head off
future economic crises.
</P>
<P>
"We must do more to build a modern framework for the global
markets of the 21st century and to limit the swings of boom and
bust that destroy hope and diminish wealth," Brown said.
</P>
<P>
The G7 joint proposals are:
</P>
<P>
--Setting up a new IMF (International Monetary Fund) fund worth
90 billion U.S. dollars for emergency lending to stop a crisis
spreading into other economies.
</P>
<P>
-- Tighter regulation of the world's international capital
markets to prevent repeat of the recent financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
-- Setting up a code of practice for private banks and
businesses, designed to regulate highly leveraged companies like
hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
-- Formulating "transparency rules" for companies to make
finaNcial transactions and dangers to the markets more visible.
</P>
<P>
-- Setting up an international code of conduct for monetary and
financial policy in G7 countries and new rules for monitoring
international capital flows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
