<HEADLINE> ECOWAS to Set Up Mediation Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 30 (Xinhua) -- A mediation and security council
will be established under a draft mechanism for conflict
prevention, management and resolution for the west African
region, the New Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
NAN quoted sources in capital Abuja as saying that foreign
ministers of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) discussed the situation in Guinea Bissau as well as the
crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
At the just-ended meeting, foreign ministers discussed the
sub-regional draft mechanism which was proposed by ministers of
defense, internal affairs and security at their July meeting in
Banjul, the Gambia.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism provides for the establishment of the mediation
council comprising nine member countries which will take
emergency decisions on threats to the sub-regional security on
behalf of member countries.
</P>
<P>
The council whose members will be elected for a two-year term
will be complemented by a council of elders whose members are
required to play the role of mediator and arbiter on such
threats.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, foreign ministers endorsed the name ECOMOG
(west African peacekeeping force) to designate the military
instrument of ECOWAS which has been used as an ad hoc force for
the restoration of peace in Liberia and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Cote d'Ivoire, the Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Mali and Niger have
pledged additional troops for ECOMOG at the request of ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers urged member countries to convene a
meeting of their military experts to determine their needs for
submission to donor organizations and ensure collective
definition of the responsibility of such troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
