<HEADLINE> S. African Job Summit Agrees on Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 30 (Xinhua) -- South African government,
business and labor Friday agreed on a broad action plan to tackle
the country's gigantic problem of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The action plan included an ambitious housing project, an
adjustment of the country's macro-economic strategy, a
strengthening of customs control and a dramatic expansion of
state-backed job creation programs.
</P>
<P>
In a 94-page declaration, participants of Friday's
presidential job summit committed themselves to addressing
joblessness, now officially at 33 percent or 4.67 million people.
</P>
<P>
The declaration commits government to reviewing its growth,
employment and redistribution (Gear) macro-economic policy. It
concedes Gear's targets would not be met.
</P>
<P>
"Adjustments to this are necessary, and detailed work will be
done to address these changed circumstances while retaining the
coherence and strength of our policy," the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin
indicated a substantive review of Gear could be under
consideration. While government still believed Gear's objectives
were correct, the policy itself may not be sustainable, he said.
</P>
<P>
The most substantive job creation measure announced at the
summit was a national project aimed at building 150,000 houses
for low-income families by December 2001.
</P>
<P>
The first phase was expected to yield about 50,000 houses and
to cost 2.5 billion Rand (440 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The program will be jointly funded by government, labor and
business. About 75 percent of the houses will be rented out, and
the rest sold.
</P>
<P>
Participants agreed to embark on a "buy South Africa" campaign
as soon as possible to promote demand for local products and
services.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed that the flow of illegal imported goods into
South Africa had to be curbed, and that customs control had to be
strengthened. The government has allocated 734.7 million Rand
(129 million Dollars) for this purpose over a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
Among the agreements reached after months of negotiations is a
framework for a social plan aimed at avoiding job losses wherever
possible, and on a comprehensive social security system for the
poor and unemployed. An investigation into the feasibility of a
basic income grant is to be undertaken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
