<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The European Union (EU) has granted Egypt loans of 714
million European currency units (ECU) (858 million U.S. dollars)
from 1993 to 1997, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A report of the EU was quoted as saying the loans granted
through the European Investment Bank have been used in projects in
transportation, communications, small and intermediary enterprises
and environment protection.
</P>
<P>
The bank has also invested more than 1.3 billion ECUs (1.5
billion dollars) since 1978 in Egypt's potable water projects,
energy, drainage system, industrial projects and communications,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwaiti government will discuss how to
reactivate the Kuwait Stock Exchange (KSE), Commerce and Industry
Minister Abdel Aziz Al-Dekheel said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The minister made his remarks after KSE index lost 41.3 points
last Wednesday to close at 1,896.7 points, the lowest level in 21
months.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Kuwait News Agency, the minister said the
government will encourage the shareholding companies to play a
more active role in investments, issue transferable bonds and
allow foreign investors to deal in KSE.
</P>
<P>
The minister voiced optimism that KSE would overcome its
downward trend and hoped dealers would regain their confidence in
the market.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh met here
Thursday evening with his Iranian counterpart Mohammad
Shariatmadar on means of enhancing bilateral trade ties, the Iraqi
News Agency (INA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to INA after the meeting, Shariatmadar said that his
country tried to promote its trade relations with Iraq and the
trade delegation he led would discuss with the Iraqi side topics
that would contribute to enhancing bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister arrived here Thursday evening heading
a 37-member commercial delegation to participate in the 31st
Baghdad International Fair due to Start on November 1.
</P>
<P>
INA said the two trade ministers would hold formal talks on
means of expanding economic and commercial cooperation between the
two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Iran will participate in the fair in a large pavilion
containing samples of food, drug, car and agricultural equipment,
INA said. 
</P>
