<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 21st ECOWAS Summit Opens in Abuja </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, Nigeria, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The 21st summit of the
Economic Community of the West African States (ECOWAS) opened in
Nigerian capital Abuja Friday to discuss the economic and
political situation in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Making the welcome speech, Nigerian Head of State and current
chairman of the ECOWAS, General Abdulsalam Abubakar said it is
the first time on the continent that leaders of different
sub-regional bodies were together to share their experiences on
political and economic development and thus strengthen the
efforts to bring about the renewed African Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar noted that various economies in the West African
sub-region have managed to maintained a level of stability since
1993 despite armed conflicts in some member countries.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the growth rate in 1997 for the whole
sub-region was 4.3 percent, as against 4.2 in the previous year,
</P>
<P>
He expressed the optimism that the growth rate which has been
on the rise since 1993 will continue to increase in the years
ahead.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar announced that significant progress has been made in
the various aspects of sub-regional economic integration,
including the ECOWAS travelers' check and the West African Gas
Pipeline Project will deliver Nigeria's rich natural gas
resources to neighboring Benin, Ghana, Togo and probably Cote
d'lvoire.
</P>
<P>
He urged member countries to remove various illegal check
points on their borders so that the free movement of persons and
goods within the sub-region which has been in effect since 1980
would be faithfully implemented,
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also urged member countries to approve the protocol
establishing the 0,5 percent Community Levy on imports from
non-member countries to relieve the fund shortage of the ECOWAS,
which was hindering the implementation of its many programs.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 16 member countries, Secretary-General of the
African Unity Organization (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim and a
representative of the United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan
were at the opening ceremony at the ECOWAS Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Also present were South African President Nelson Mandela, who
was representing the South African Development Community, and a
representative of Zambian President Fredrick Chiluba, chairman of
the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the ECOWAS chairman also expressed his concern
over the conflicts in Guinea Bissau, the Great Lakes region and
other parts of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar called for the establishment of a permanent mechanism
for conflict prevention, management and resolution in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
His proposal received support from OAU chief Salim, who also
spoke on the occasion, and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
whose representative delivered a message on his behalf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
