<HEADLINE> Ugandans Urged to Maintain Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Prime Minister Kintu
Musoke has called for serious efforts in the districts to ensure
that all categories of roads are in a serviceable condition at
all times.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister issued the call when opening a two-day road
strategy workshop here recently, Radio Uganda reported Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation, upgrading and maintenance of roads will
continue to rank high in the government's top priorities, he
said.
</P>
<P>
A good road network is important for Uganda's development
because roads account for over 90 percent of the movement of the
country's goods.
</P>
<P>
At the workshop, Minister of Works, Housing and Communications
John Nasasira asked district leaders to stop awarding themselves
feeder road contracts because they cannot supervise themselves.
</P>
<P>
Grants from the central government for roads in the districts
will be suspended if the rule is not adhered to, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Most feeder roads in Uganda were seriously destroyed by the
heavy rains last year. The poor conditions of roads denied local
produce's easy access to markets and pose a big challenge to the
country's trade and security. 
</P>
