<HEADLINE> West African travelers' Checks Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, Nigeria, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The much-expected West
African travelers' checks were launched Friday in Nigerian
capital Abuja at the opening ceremony of the 21st summit of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the Committee of Governors of ECOWAS
Central Banks, governor of the Nigerian Central Bank Paul Oguwuma
said the event is a major step towards ECOWAS's goal of building
a single monetary zone by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The check is issued by the West African Monetary Agency
(WAMA), formerly the West African Clearing House, under the
auspices of the above-mentioned ECOWAS committee. It is designed
to promote and facilitate trade, tourist and other service
transactions within the West African sub-region.
</P>
<P>
According to Oguwuma, it should be seen as the precursor of
the future common currency of ECOWAS countries. He urged all
member central banks to make their best endeavors to facilitate
the widespread use of the travelers' checks to foster the
intra-regional payment system.
</P>
<P>
The travelers' check is denominated in 5, 10, 20, 50 and 100
West African Units of Account (WAUA). A WAUA is equivalent to
1.36 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The check is fully convertible into national currencies of
ECOWAS's 16 member countries, the rate of which will be published
by the WAMA weekly, said Oguwuma. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
