<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Economic Adjustment Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of
Finance Sufian Ahmed said Friday that the government of Ethiopia
has recently adopted a new medium-term economic adjustment
program for 1998/99-2000/01.
</P>
<P>
Opening the eighth annual conference of the Ethiopian Economic
Association in Nazareth, 90 kms southeast of Addis Ababa,
Minister Sufian said the program aims at reducing poverty through
broad-based economic growth in a stable macro-economic
environment, according to the Ethiopian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Sufian noted that the program will also design policies to
maintain financial stability and further deregulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
In Addition, Sufian said the adjustment program specifies
sectoral policies and strategies that are deemed to enhance
macro-economic stability and growth.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that major elements of the program include,
among others, the acceleration of privatization, further
liberalization of the exchange regime, civil service reform and
rehabilitation of the environment.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the program envisages an average
annual growth rate of real gross domestic product (GDP) at seven
percent, annual average rate of inflation at three percent,
external current account deficit at about nine percent of the
GDP, and the net foreign asset of the banking system on average
at four months import.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that the government will further
encourage private investment to attain the afore-mentioned
targets.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference is being held under the theme "the
Ethiopian economy: performance and evaluation".
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier report here, the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) has approved the program and will finance 42
million U.S. Dollars in 1998/99 financial year ending July 7,
1999 in support of the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
