<HEADLINE> Annan Praises Glenn as "Pioneer for Longevity" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Friday sent a congratulatory message to John Glenn,
an outgoing U.S. senator who returned to space after 36 years at
the age of 77, saying he has become "a pioneer for longevity."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman's office, Annan said,
"On behalf of the United Nations, congratulations on yet another
triumph in a long and heroic career. The world knows you as a
pioneer of the space age."
</P>
<P>
Annan said in the statement, "You have now become a pioneer for
longevity. Returning to outer space at age 77, you are helping to
launch the United Nations International Year of Older Persons, to
be celebrated in 1999."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.N. chief voiced his "best wishes for a safe
return," saying that "the United Nations is with you all the way."
</P>
<P>
Cheered on by an enthralled nation, Glenn blasted off from the
U.S. Kennedy Space Center at 2:19 p.m. EST (1919 GMT) to become
the oldest person to fly in space -- more than twice the age of
the youngest of his six fellow crew members.
</P>
<P>
Glenn was the first U.S. astronaut to orbit the earth in 1962.
</P>
<P>
During the nine-day mission, the outgoing senator from Ohio,
the U.S., who lobbied for years to get the American space
authorities to let him fly again, will be a guinea pig for
experiments in the ageing process. He will give daily blood
samples for muscle wasting studies and sleep in a cap wired to
measure his brain waves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
