<HEADLINE> China on Impact of Globalization, Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 30 (xinhua) -- The impact of
globalization and liberalization on the countries is complex,
varied and uneven, China said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 53rd session of the U.N.General Assembly,
Chinese delegate Yuan Shaofu said the weak economic foundation of
the developing countries and their inferior competitive position
dictated that in the short and medium term, they would benefit
little from liberalization, with the Least Developed Countries at
particular risk of being further marginalized.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Shaofu said the Asian financial crisis gave a cautionary
story about the bumpy road taken by the developing countries in
their effort to open up their markets and showed the negative
impact of and unpredictable risks associated with globalization
and liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Yuan said that as an important tool in promoting globalization
and liberalization, the Multilateral Trading System had played a
role in settling international trade disputes and reducing general
tariff levels.
</P>
<P>
However, Yuan said, as proved by the fact, the present system
had neither solved a number of critical problems involved in
international trade nor reflected in a balanced way the interests
of all sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
