<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Commemorative Stamps Launched in Abuja </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, Nigeria, October 30 (Xinhua) -- A set of two
commemorative stamps on the west African peace-keeping force
ECOMOG were launched Friday at the opening ceremony of the summit
of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) here.
</P>
<P>
The stamps, one carrying the national flags of ECOWAS's 16
member countries and denominated 50 Naira (one U.S. Dollar equals
to 85 Naira), and another depicting the warship used for ECOMOG
operations and denominated five Naira, are produced by the
Nigerian Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
All the other 15 member countries are also expected to issue
similar stamps to commemorate EC0MOG's eight years of successful
operation.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG was first formed in 1990 to intervene in the Liberian
civil war. It has successfully brought an end to the war and
eventually led to a free and fair election, from which emerged
the government of Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
After the coup in May 1997 in Sierra Leone, ECOMOG troops were
sent there, where it also succeeded by ousting the military junta
of Major Paul Johnny Koroma and reinstating elected civilian
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Today, ECOMOG troops are still fighting the remnants of Koroma
and his ally of the Revolutionary united Front who wage a
guerrilla warfare in the mountainous areas in eastern Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
And with the four-month-old conflicts in Guinea Bissau between
President Joao Bernardo Vieira and uprising army general Ansumane
Mane, the on-going ECOWAS summit is expected to discuss the
possibility of deploying ECOMOG to that troubled member state.
</P>
<P>
According to Canice Umenwaliri, the Nigerian Minister of
Communications, who spoke on the launching ceremony, ECOMOG is
now "universally recognized as one of the most successful
sub-regional efforts of its kind ever mounted in Africa or
elsewhere in the world."
</P>
<P>
The stamps, he said, highlight for posterity, the sacrifice
and achievement of ECOMOG in Liberia and Sierra Leone and is also
another way of expressing the appreciation of the government and
people of Nigeria to ECOMOG participants.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria contributed most of the troops and resources to
ECOMOG. Ten other ECOWAS member countries as well as Uganda and
Tanzania also contributed troops.
</P>
<P>
All these countries as well as the nine successive commanders
of ECOMOG were awarded at the ceremony held at the ECOWAS
Secretariat in Abuja. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Cites 24 Instances of Alleged Leaks in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- A federal judge cited 24
instances of alleged grand jury leaks to the news media in
ordering an investigation of whether Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr's office violated secrecy rules, newly unsealed court
documents revealed Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson found "a prima facie
violation" of grand jury secrecy rules starting January 21, the
day the Monica Lewinsky scandal erupted in news reports.
</P>
<P>
Some of the reports over the following five months referred to
"federal law enforcement sources" and "sources close to
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr" as providing the
information.
</P>
<P>
Johnson noted that a television network news report "explicitly
identifies `prosecutors' as disclosing evidence gathered as part
of the grand jury investigation."
</P>
<P>
The story was a January 22 account on NBC of the "talking
points" document that Lewinsky said she wrote so that friend Linda
Tripp could provide testimony in the Paula Jones case that would
be helpful to President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"This evidence, the `talking points' document, was likely to be
presented to the grand jury," Johnson wrote. "The law in this
circuit makes it perfectly clear that government attorneys may not
reveal documentary evidence that is likely to be presented to the
grand jury."
</P>
<P>
In the September 24 decision, made public Friday, Johnson
ordered that an outside expert be appointed to assist her
investigation into whether Starr's office illegally leaked grand
jury evidence.
</P>
<P>
"Due to serious and repetitive prima facie violations" of grand
jury secrecy rules, "a complete and thorough review of these
allegations must be undertaken," the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
The outside expert, whose name was deleted from the newly
released papers, has wide-ranging authority to subpoena documents
from Starr's office and question current or former members of
Starr's staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
