<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Privatize Kilimanjaro Int'l Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The Kilimanjaro Airport
Development Company (KADCO) is scheduled to take over the
state-owned Kilimanjaro International Airport (KIA) in north
Tanzania next month.
</P>
<P>
The company will invest between 25 and 27 billion Shillings
(between 37 and 40 million U.S. Dollars) in two years, Director
of Planning and Research at the Ministry of Communications and
Transport Abisai N. Temba told reporters Friday.
</P>
<P>
Temba said that the investment will be made in, among other
things, the refurbishment of the entire runway, apron, taxi way,
rehabilitation of the terminal building and improvement of the
navigation aids.
</P>
<P>
Money will also be spent on building a 200-room tourist hotel
in the vicinity of KIA, he said, adding that the first guest is
expected to enter the hotel before June of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
KADCO is a locally registered company formed by Messrs Mott
McDonald International of Britain, which negotiated with the
Tanzanian government over a period and signed a 25-year
concession agreement last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, he said, within 20 months from the
initial date of cooperation, KADCO should advertize KIA in
international newspapers, magazines and electronic media
throughout the world in order to attract traffic business.
</P>
<P>
He said that traffic control at the airport will be exercised
by KADCO while upper air aircraft management will fall under the
Civil Aviation Authority.
</P>
<P>
According to plans the would-be KIA owner is also expected to
put up an 18-hole golf course in the vicinity of the airport, the
ministry director noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a statement issued by the ministry said KIA will be
the first international airport to be privatized in eastern and
southern Africa. The government will entrust the existing assets
to KADCO in exchange for a minority share-holding in KADCO.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that this demonstrates the commitment of
the government to work with international investors to improve
the quality of national infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
A modern and vibrant international airport in Kilimanjaro will
boost the development of tourism in the northern circuit of
Tanzania, ministry officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
