<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Extends MINURSO's Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Friday unanimously adopted a resolution, extending the
mandate of the United Nations Mission for the Referendum in
Western Sahara (MINURSO) until December 17.
</P>
<P>
The resolution reiterated the Security Council's commitment "to
assist the parties to achieve a just and lasting solution to the
question of Western Sahara."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council adopted the resolution after its
closed-door consultations on a report presented by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who proposed a green light to the
identification of potential voters in three tribal groups in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The 470-member MINURSO has been stationed in the territory for
the past seven years. Its current mandate expires on October 31.
</P>
<P>
The resolution welcomed "the stated intentions of the
Government of Morocco and the Polisario Front to cooperate
actively with the MINURSO in implementing the proposals" contained
in Annan's report.
</P>
<P>
The resolution called on the parties concerned to agree by
mid-November on a package, which covers the identification
process, the memorandum pertaining to the activities of the office
of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also extended a welcome to "the agreement of the
Moroccan authorities to formalize the presence of the UNHCR in the
Western Sahara, and the agreement of the Polisario Front to resume
pre-registration activities in the refugee camps."
</P>
<P>
In his report presented to the Security Council, Annan Tuesday
proposed a green light to voter registration of members of three
Western Sahara tribal groups involved in a dispute that has held
up a referendum on the future of the territory.
</P>
<P>
The referendum is to decide whether Western Sahara should be
incorporated into Morocco, which controls most of the former
Spanish colony, or become independent, as sought by the Polisario
Front, whose base camps are in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Morocco maintained that all members of those groups had a right
to be identified to determine their eligibility to vote. However,
the Polisario Front said none had that right except for those
listed in a 1974 Spanish census of the territory, and their
immediate families.
</P>
<P>
To break the deadlock, Annan said in his latest report, "I have
decided to present my own arbitration in order to move ahead on
this issue."
</P>
<P>
The referendum is likely to be held in December 1999, a year
later than the most recent target date of December 7 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
