<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt Urged to Restrict Unplanned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government was
urged Friday to restrict the mushrooming of unplanned buildings
in the country especially in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
President of the Zambian Institute of Architects (ZIA) Dixon
Bwalya made the appeal here while opening a two-day workshop for
architects.
</P>
<P>
He said ZIA is concerned at the mushrooming of the unplanned
buildings especially in the capital city of Lusaka, which he
said has made the city look ugly.
</P>
<P>
The unplanned expansion of Lusaka coupled with other factors
such as the lack of adequate clean water, poor drainage system
and the potential fire hazards to structures has continued to
worry his institute, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bwalya accused councillors of allowing the structures to
mushroom up hazardously around the city, making it look like a
huge ghetto.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to come up with minimum qualifications
for councillors to ensure that quality people who know about town
planning can be elected.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion Minister of Local Government and Housing
Bennie Mwiinga acknowledged the problem of the unplanned
structures in the city in particular and the country as a whole,
but challenged the architects to help find a solution to the
scourge. 
</P>
