<HEADLINE> Ghana's Major Power Supplier Loses $17m </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's main supplier of
electric power, Volta River Authority (VRA), said it has lost 40
billion Cedis (about 17 million U.S. Dollars) this year due to
low volume of production caused by lack of rains.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Quayson, Chairman of Energy Foundation told reporters
in the eastern port city of Tema that VRA's volume of production
dropped by 30 percent, a special story by Ghana News Agency (GNA)
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The company's sister organization, Electricity Company,
general distributors of power also suffered similar losses,
Quayson said, but he did not immediately give figures.
</P>
<P>
He said the foundation has embarked on a program aimed at
reducing domestic consumption and commended VALCO, aluminum
smelters, for using power efficiently. 
