<HEADLINE> 2,000 kg of Drugs Set Afire in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, Nigeria, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Flames shot up into the
sky here Friday as about 2,000 kilograms of Indian hemps, heroine
and other drugs were set afire by leaders of member countries of
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
The event, a major one at the opening session of the 2lst
ECOWAS summit held in the Nigerian capital, is an indication of
the sub-regional leaders' determination to combat the rapid
spread of drug trafficking and abuse in their countries.
</P>
<P>
The drugs, seized by authorities in ECOWAS 16 member
countries, were set on flames by leaders in front of the ECOWAS
Secretariat in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement read at the ceremony, the leaders
expressed their deep concern over the spread of drug abuse and
trafficking in West Africa and the resultant upsurge in criminal
activities.
</P>
<P>
The leaders promised to allocate necessary resources and to
adopt legislative measures and the operational instruments needed
to protect their people from the destructive effects of drugs and
related criminal activities,
</P>
<P>
To step up the war against drugs, the leaders are expected to
approve the formal establishment of an ECOWAS drug fund during
the on-going summit, which will end Saturday. 
</P>
