<HEADLINE> Zambia, Angola Reaffirms Commitment to Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Zambia and Angola reaffirmed
Friday their commitment to strengthening peace efforts and
stability and their support for embattled Congolese (K) leader
Laurent Kabila, according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 15th Angola-Zambia Joint Permanent Commission
on Defense and Security that opened in Lusaka, Zambian Defense
Minister Chitalu Sampa said Zambia is committed to the attainment
of peace in Angola and that the Zambian government will ensure
that the the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol to end the Angolan civil
war is implemented to the letter.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, he noted, has put in place tough measures to ensure
that unscrupulous arms dealers do not use the country's soil or
airspace to supply arms to the rebel movement, the National Union
for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), led by Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Among the security measures that Zambia has put in place are
increased security at airports and landing strips countrywide and
border areas, Sampa said.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Angola accused Zambia of supplying UNITA with
arms and once threatened to invade its eastern neighbor. Lusaka
denied the accusation and allowed Luanda as well as U.N.
officials to come to the country to inspect the border areas.
</P>
<P>
The tension between the two countries did not ease until U.N.
officials said the Zambian government was innocent.
</P>
<P>
As far as the regional conflicts, Sampa said the emerging
political and armed conflicts are hampering the efforts by the
14-member Southern African Development Community (SADC) states to
attain regional development and stability.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for member states to support all the
peace efforts aimed at solving conflicts in countries such as
Congo (K), Lesotho and the possibly renewed civil war between
UNITA and the Angolan government troops.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian minister also praised Angola for sending troops to
help Kabila quell the Congolese rebellion which started on August
2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
He added that there is need for the joint commission to
continue meeting regularly to discuss common border problems to
enhance peace and stability between the two countries and the
entire region.
</P>
<P>
At the same meeting, Angolan Defense Minister General Pedro
Sebastiao urged SADC countries to treat UNITA leader Savimbi as a
war criminal for violating the Lusaka protocol.
</P>
<P>
He said Savimbi is rebuilding his army and that a number of
people and property are being devastated in the renewed fighting.
</P>
<P>
UNITA, said the Angolan minister, poses a threat not only to
Angola, adding that the movement is also creating alliances with
other rebel movements to destabilize the region.
</P>
<P>
Sebastiao urged SADC countries to unite against UNITA and
neutralize all military aggression by the organization.
</P>
<P>
He also defended the build-up of Angolan government forces in
Congo (K), saying Kabila's government is "legitimate" and branded
Rwanda and Uganda, which denied Kinshasa's allegations of backing
Congolese rebels, as aggressors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
