<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Palestine Soon Submits Plan Against Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. said on Friday that
a Palestinian plan of action against terrorists who have attacked
Israel was on track and would be submitted to the United States
soon.
</P>
<P>
However, U.S. Presidential National Security Council advisor
Sandy Berger did not specify when the plan would be presented. It
is due by Monday, when the land-for-security agreement between
Israel and the Palestinian Authority takes effect.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians and the Israelis are discussing this and we
are working with the Palestinians," Berger told a news conference
at the National Press Club here.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is on track, and I think we will see it soon," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the State Department said the plan, which Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has made a prerequisite for an
Israeli pullback on the West Bank, would be ready Friday.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, a suicide bomber attempted to attack a school bus
carrying Israeli children in Palestinian-run Gaza. The terrorist
and an Israeli soldier were killed. The children were not hurt.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, the Islamic fundamentalist group, claimed
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian authorities confined Hamas founder Ahmed Yassin to
his home and cut his telephone lines. Palestinian security
officials also said that more than 100 Hamas activists had been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
Berger credited the Palestinian Authority with taking quite
vigorous action, and called on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and other Arab leaders to support the agreement signed by
Palestinians and Israelis last week.
</P>
<P>
"They have been quite legitimately unhappy over the past 18
months that the peace process has been stalled," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
"The process is now on track, in an agreement that Chairman
(Yasser) Arafat himself, I think who is the best judge of the
interests of the Palestinian people, believes is a good
agreement," he added.
</P>
<P>
"It's important that the moderate Arab countries support that.
And we have seen much stronger statements of support, for example,
from the Gulf state countries," he affirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
