<HEADLINE> Clinton: G7 Financial Ministers to Work to Calm Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The finance ministers from
the Group of Seven industrial nations will work on new and
concrete plans to help calm world financial markets, said U.S.
President Bill Clinton here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to ask our finance ministers to make new and
very concrete recommendations to help contain the excessive
volatility in financial markets that can destroy hope and diminish
wealth," he told reporters after G7 finance ministers and Central
Bank governors issued joint proposals in London to deal with world
financial chaos.
</P>
<P>
The G7 plan is targeted at keeping tighter checks on
destabilizing flows of hot money and providing the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) with a new mechanism to assist crisis-stricken
countries.
</P>
<P>
"This line of credit gives us a powerful new tool that can be
used when it will do the most good, at the lowest cost, before the
trouble starts," said Clinton, who was speaking to reporters
before departing the White House for a trip to New York.
</P>
<P>
The United States had originally put forward such a
"precautionary" fund earlier this month. The U.S. Congress later
passed a bill which contains the provision of contributing some
17.9 billion dollars for the IMF. That is part of a global 90
billion dollar package to replenish IMF resources depleted by over
110 billion dollars in bailouts put together since the financial
crisis first erupted in Thailand 15 months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
