<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong will Play More Roles in Future: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 31 (Xinhua) --International experts
attending a seminar here have expressed their confidence that Hong
Kong has good prospect and will play more roles in future after
its return to China.
</P>
<P>
They put forth their views and ideas at the last session
Saturday morning of the three-day conference titled "Hong Kong in
China: A Year Later" after listening to papers presented by their
Hong Kong and Singapore fellows in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The conference was held by the East Asian Institute of the
National University of Singapore and Some 60 scholars, experts and
professors from Hong Kong, Singapore, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Thailand, Japan, China and Taiwan took part in the event designed
to review what has happened in Hong Kong since China recovered
sovereignty over it on July 1, 1997.  Reviewing scenario in Hong
Kong a year after its return to China, all the speakers lauded the
result of the implementation of the Basic Law on Hong Kong and the
successes of China's formula of "one country two systems".
</P>
<P>
Just as Dr. Ow Chin Hock, minister of state for Foreign
Affairs, pointed out at opening of the conference that "It is
heartening to see that the soul and essence of Hong Kong have not
changed or have been changed in any fundamental way."
</P>
<P>
"One country two systems is working. Hong Kong people are
running Hong Kong," he quoted what Hong Kong's Chief Secretary
Mrs. Anson Chan has said to support his view point.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Dr. Jusuf Wanandi, chairman of the Supervisory
Board of the Center for Strategic and International Studies,
Indonesia, arrived at a conclusion that "Hong Kong will continue
to play an important role in the region."
</P>
<P>
"The region, including Indonesia, should give due attention to
her during the transition and even more so in the future," he
underlined.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Stephen Leong, from the Institute of Strategic and
International Studies, Malaysia, said "Malaysians are optimistic
that the SAR (Special Administrative Region of China) would
succeed in its transition."
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia perceived an unmistakable air of confidence in Hong
Kong, " Dr. Leong said, "They felt assured that the SAR would
perform well."
</P>
<P>
Professor Umphon Phanachet, director of the Chinese Studies
Center of the Institute of Asian Studies of the Chulalongkorn
University, Thailand, said "since July 1, 1997, Hong Kong Special
Administration Region (SAR) has undergone many challenges, indeed,
many more than most people had expected."
</P>
<P>
"But the SAR Government deserves praises for its comparatively
smooth implementation of the first ever of its kind of one country
two systems model," the professor said.
</P>
<P>
"The Central People's Government in Beijing should also be
commended with its strict adherence to the spirit of the Basic
Law," he added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that "Hong Kong is positioned well regionally and
globally," Phanachet concluded "Hong Kong seems to have the
capacity and the track records to be among the first to take
advantage of the regional recovery when it inevitably comes."
</P>
<P>
In his paper analyzing Hong Kong's position on the boards of
the region and the world, Japanese professor Takeshi Hamashita
from the Institute of Oriental Culture, Tokyo University, said
"geoeconomically speaking, Hong Kong is becoming to play more
important role in intra-Asia relation and in other world."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is being Asianized relating from southeast Asia to
northeast Asia," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He expects Hong Kong to maintain the role to intermediate
east-west relations and to strengthen intermediary ties within
Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Along with Re-Asianization of Hong Kong, Hong Kong will play
much more important intermediary roll within intra-Asian regional
relations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Gerald Chan, visiting research fellow of the East Asian
Institute of the National University of Singapore, said "both
Australia and New Zealand, together with most of other countries
in the world, recognize the attractiveness of Hong Kong's low
level of taxation and its role as a service and entrepot center
for trade with China."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong remains crucial as a gateway and facilitator for
Sino-Australia as well as Sino-New Zealand trade, " he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
