<HEADLINE> Russia Vows to Curb Inflation Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Russian Economy Minister Andrei
Shapovalyants said Saturday that the government will endeavor to
keep the country's inflation under 30 percent next year with its
economic stabilization measures.
</P>
<P>
However, the optimistic assertion was disputed by Dmitry
Vasilyev, chairman of the Russian Federal Securities Commission.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said the government's stabilization plan, with
measures calling for major expenses, including wage and pension
hikes, payment of government bonds, will end with the printing of
more rubles,
</P>
<P>
"We need to be honest," the Interfax news agency quoted him as
saying.
</P>
<P>
To raise the minimum wage and the minimum pension to
subsistence level, a 400 percent increase was needed, Vasilyev
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Prime Minister Valentina Matviyenio, the
Russian government owes its citizens 70.5 billion rubles (4.41
billion U.S. dollars) in pensions, back wages and children's
allowances.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, most of the state debt on Treasury bills is
supposed to be repaid in rubles, Vasilyev said.
</P>
<P>
If the measure is endorsed, an additional 200 billion rubles
(12.5 billion dollars) will have to be printed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
