<HEADLINE> Parti Quebecois Leads in Quebec Election Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The Parti Quebecois (PQ) has
taken a narrow lead in popular support four weeks before a general
election in Canada's French-speaking province of Quebec, according
to a poll published Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the separatist PQ overtook the
federal Liberal Party in dozens of polls since early this year.
The November 30 election is believed to have great impact on the
future of Quebec and all of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The ruling PQ promised that if elected, it will strive to
create winning conditions for another referendum on Quebec's
succession from Canada.
</P>
<P>
The poll, the first since the election was called Wednesday,
found that the PQ had the backing of 47.5 percent of decided
voters, while the Liberals were supported by 46.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Another 5.7 percent would vote for Action Democratique and 0.6
percent picked other parties, according to the poll conducted by
Groupe Leger and Leger for Le Journal de Montreal and The Globe
and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Among francophone voters, who constitute about 80 percent of
the electorate, 55.9 percent said they would pick the PQ, 37.3
percent favored the Liberals and 6.2 percent cited Action
Democratique.
</P>
<P>
"The PQ's wide advantage among francophone voters puts it in
the best position to win a majority of seats" in the 125-seat
Quebec National Assembly, said Canada's leading paper, the Globe
and Mail.
</P>
<P>
However, there is potential for a major shift in voter support,
since 33.3 percent of the decided voters said their choice could
change between now and the election at the end of next month, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted from October 28 to 30, has a margin of
error of 3.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Decides to Suspend Relations With UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced on Saturday
that it has decided to suspend all its relations with the
U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq (UNSCOM) until the
commission has been restructured and its Chairman Richard Butler
has been removed.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency reported that the decision was made
at a joint meeting of the Revolutionary Command Council and
the ruling Baath Party, chaired by President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The joint meeting said in a statement the decision would
not be applied to the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA),
another U.N. agency assigned with the mission of counting for
and destroying Iraq's nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Iraq is to freeze all activities of
UNSCOM in Iraq including its monitoring mission starting from
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi move came as a surprise to most political observes
as the U.N. Security Council just indicated a day ago in a letter
to the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan that it was ready to
begin the comprehensive review as soon as the U.N. chief confirms
that the U.N. arms inspectors are receiving full cooperation from
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on August 5 suspended cooperation with UNSCOM and IAEA,
barring them from carrying out on-the-spot inspections to new
sites. However, their monitoring activities were still allowed.
</P>
<P>
Explaining its August 5 decision, the Iraqi government accused
UNSCOM and Butler of being a tool in the hand of America and
serving American interests and trying to create pretext to prolong
the U.N. economic sanctions imposed on the country for eight years.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi government then demanded that UNSCOM be restructured, its
headquarters be moved to Vienna or Geneva to be away from American
direct influence and the office of Chairman of UNSCOM rotate among
the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council responded on September 9 by freezing its
periodic review of the sanctions regime, thereby keeping Iraq
under the U.N. sanctions indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership said in the statement "events of this year
have revealed two serious facts. First is the American lies about
the Iraqi Presidential sites which put the affairs on the brink of
destructive war."
</P>
<P>
Last February, the United States and Britain alleged that
chemical and biological weapons were hidden in Iraq's presidential
sites and threatened to launch air strikes against Iraq to force
it into agreeing to open those presidential sites to U.N. arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Later a special group comprising senior diplomats from member
states of the U.N. Security Council and weapons inspectors working
for UNSCOM inspected those sites, but found nothing.
</P>
<P>
"When the truth (about presidential sites) had been unveiled
before the whole world, America was not punished for its lies and
no step had been adopted towards the lifting of the embargo," said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Second is filthy game played by UNSCOM and its chief in
coordination with the U.S. about the allegations of the VX (nerve
gas) and when the truth had appeared through neutral labs in France
and Switzerland, the UNSCOM chief has not admitted the fact, but
he went on asking Iraq for what he termed further clarifications
with the aim of procrastination and distorting facts," it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement complained that "no deterrent measures had been
taken against Butler for his lying and manipulation with facts."
</P>
<P>
A U.S. army laboratory said June that it found traces of VX on
samples of Iraq warhead fragments it analyzed.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused the U.S. of faking the results and insisted that
French and Swiss laboratories re-test them. Butler finally agreed
to the Iraqi requirement but said he believed Iraq had weaponized
VX agent and demand Iraq account for its past chemical program.
</P>
<P>
123 samples from different areas of a warhead dump in Iraq were
then given to Swiss and French labs and American labs for a second
round of tests.
</P>
<P>
Tests of 40 samples from Switzerland proved negative as did
the second round of U.S. tests from other 43 samples.
</P>
<P>
Of the 40 samples tested in French labs, 39 proved negative.
Scientists found a "degradation product" of a nerve agent in one
sample, which could be VX, or other nerve agents called Sarin or
Soman.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the U.N. Security Council, UNSCOM said Iraq had
probably hidden information on its ability to put VX into warheads
and now had to account for its past program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Commission Head Visits Central Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Governor of central China's Hubei
Province Jiang Zhuping, who met Jacques Santer, the President of
the European Commission here this afternoon, said that EU member
states have put more than 700 million U.S. dollars worth of
investment in over 200 projects in the province.
</P>
<P>
He said that province's trade with Europe last year was worth
more than 400 million U.S. dollars and in the first nine months of
this year it was more than 360 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also described the fight against floods, the loss of
lives and money, and the rebuilding in Hubei, which was heavily
hit by this summer's flooding.
</P>
<P>
Santer said that the province is a developmental model of
relations between the EU and China and trade between Hubei and the
EU is a miniature version of EU-China trade.
</P>
<P>
The EU is expected to replace Japan as China's second largest
trade partner this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Santer said that the EU wants to build a comprehensive
partnership with China and that he wants to learn more about
China's economic achievements through his visit.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his sympathy with the Hubei for the losses during
the flooding, Santer said that the province is a successful
example of China's economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
