<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. Newspapers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The world's leading industrial nations endorsed U.S.
President Bill Clinton's proposal to help protect vulnerable but
essentially healthy nations from the kind of currency and stock
market upheavals that have battered nations from Asia to Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
-- An 11-member panel of senior Spanish judges decided
unanimously that Spain has the legal right to bring criminal
charges against Chile's former dictator, General Augusto Pinochet,
and to seek his extradition from Britain. The judges' decision,
which is based on a large body of international humanitarian law,
contradicted a ruling by the High Court in London, which said that
Britain had no authority to arrest the general.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. economy grew at an unexpectedly strong pace in the
July-to-September period, the Commerce Department said Friday,
despite turmoil in global financial markets. The 3.3 percent
annual rate reported by the department was a full percentage point
or more higher than many analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
-- The United Nations Security Council agreed Friday on the
nature and scope of a comprehensive review of Iraq's relations
with the United Nations that the council has offered to undertake
if Baghdad complies with its orders and resumes cooperation with
U.N. weapons inspectors. 
</P>
