<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Government Approves Anti-Crisis Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government on
Saturday approved the main points of an economic crisis program
which would introduce more state control of the nation's finances.
</P>
<P>
"This does not mean giving up market relations. It means
regulating them," Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said after a
government meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said the plan was "a government document. It is not even a
program but a system of measures which will be modified and
supplemented in the course of work."
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, which will be finalized next Thursday, price
ceilings will be put on essential foods and medicines and more
support would be given to small and medium-size enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate social tension caused by the chronic non-payment
of pensions and salaries, Primakov ordered Finance Minister
Mikhail Zadornov to go on television on the last day of each month
to announce the amount of money allocated to pay in full current
salaries to public sector workers, the military and key
ministries' staffers.
</P>
<P>
"If this money is not received by some sector of our society in
some region after the finance minister has announced that, let
them look at higher levels to find out why the money has not
come," Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov also denied allegations that loans provided by the
International Monetary Fund ended up being stolen and moved to
foreign bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
"A portion of the money has gotten into the hands of dishonest
people. But the majority of the funds has been used properly," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He described the recent spate of allegations of government
corruption as "a pretext invented in order to prevent the IMF from
giving us tranches of the loans approved earlier."
</P>
<P>
The IMF, which was briefed on the government measures, voiced
objections regarding state regulation of the economy, Primakov
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that not all the recommendations by IMF experts would
be accepted.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said some recommendations ran counter to the recent
statement by IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus that
macroeconomic policies alone were not sufficient to keep the
situation under control.
</P>
<P>
Russia was a country which "has never kneeled and will never
kneel", he said. If Russia received financial support, "things
will be easier for us."
</P>
<P>
"But we will not stand on our knees and beg. Russia will get
on its feet anyway." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
