<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Challenges And Opportunities In China's Foreign Trade (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The 84th China Export
Commodity Fair, that ended in Guangzhou yesterday, repeated its 1994
record high of 11 billion U.S. dollars in business, but Chinese
trade officials are still only cautiously optimistic about the
country's trade future.
</P>
<P>
They say the results were hard-earned and point to the negative
effects of the Asian financial crisis, especially the depreciation
of currencies in neighboring countries and its impact on China's
foreign trade. And, they say, China's foreign trade will face
difficulties for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
Things began to worsen earlier this year, leading to slower
growth of exports, at 3.9 percent in the first nine months, as
compared with 24 percent for the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The fair also had a decline in the number of orders and some
prices, as some buyers turn to Southeast Asia where exports are
cheaper. At the same time, traditional exports to Southeast Asia
decreased.
</P>
<P>
However, they say they also believe that there are favorable
conditions for foreign trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Challenges and Opportunities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One advantage is that China's economy is expected to continue
to grow at an average of 7 percent for the next decade or more,
providing a basis for foreign trade development.
</P>
<P>
The stable political and economic situation in China also makes
overseas investors more confident.
</P>
<P>
The 84th export fair showed the good prospects in
newly-emerging markets, with orders from the United States and
Europe growing substantially and the Middle East and Africa
showing great potential.
</P>
<P>
It also showed the increased competitiveness of new Chinese
products and the rapid growth of overseas-funded enterprises is
believed to be another favorable factor. China has more than
145,000 joint ventures with overseas funding, whose exports and
imports for the first time have exceeded those of state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Increased government support for foreign trade enterprises,
like tax rebates, better financing, and low interest rates are
also helping foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The Asian economies are taking a turn for the better, as could
be seen at the 84th fair where orders from the Republic of Korea
rose by 16 percent and those from Southeast Asia, 30
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
