<HEADLINE> Iraq Decides to Suspend Relations With UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced on Saturday
that it has decided to suspend all its relations with the
U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq (UNSCOM), a move beyond
the expectation of the international community.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency reported that the decision was made in a
joint meeting of the Revolutionary Command Council and the ruling
Baath Party, chaired by President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The joint meeting said the decision would not be applied to the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), another U.N. agency
assigned with the mission of counting for and destroying Iraq's
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decides to freeze all UNSCOM's activities in Iraq
including its monitoring mission, said the joint meeting, adding
the decision will not be revoked before the U.N. Security Council
has removed UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler from his post and
UNSCOM has been restructured.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on August 5 suspended cooperation with UNSCOM and IAEA,
barring them from carrying out on-the-spot inspections to new
sites. However, their monitoring activities were still
unaffected. 
</P>
