<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Export Fair - China's Foreign Trade Showcase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The 84th China Export
Commodity Fair that closed yesterday in the southern Chinese city
of Guangzhou did 11 billion U.S. dollars in business, the same as
the record high at the 76th fair in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The fair has long been considered a showcase and barometer of
China's foreign trade. It started in 1957 when New China was badly
in need of a breakthrough in the political and economic blockade
of hostile outside forces.
</P>
<P>
Today, it is the largest foreign trade venue for Chinese
goods. In its 42 years, business has gone over 10 billion
U.S. dollars four times.
</P>
<P>
According to a veteran trade official, in the old days, the
trade hall was the size of 3 football fields and only had room
enough for 12,000 displays. Today, it is the size of 28 football
fields, with 100,000 items on display.
</P>
<P>
The first fair did 17.54 million U.S. dollars worth of
business, or one 627th of the 11 billion U.S. dollars at the 84th
fair.
</P>
<P>
It took 20 years for the amount of trade to reach 3 billion
U.S. dollars from that opening 17.54 million, but it took only 11
years after that for the figure to go from 4 billion dollars to 10
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Export Fair (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the 83rd fair, business with the United States also
surpassed that with Hong Kong and Macao. At the 84th, the four
largest customers were Europe, the U.S., Hong Kong and Macao, and
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The 84th fair was the first to have the Information Products
Hall, with high-tech and brand-name products. The Changhong Group,
a leading color television maker, did 40 million U.S. dollars in
business.
</P>
<P>
While the fair's trade kept growing, China's proportion was
shrinking, as a result of diversified trade. Twenty years ago, the
fair was where 40 percent of the country's export business was
conducted. Now the rate has fallen to 25 percent. And, the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation since 1980 has
approved 7 regional trade fairs that complement the Guangzhou
Fair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
