<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Meets with Yemeni Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
met on Saturday with visiting Yemeni Foreign Minister Abdul Qader
Ba-Jammal in the Red Sea resort of Sharm el Sheikh on bilateral
relations and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Ba-Jammal, also Yemen's deputy prime minister, told reporters
after the meeting that he conveyed a message to Mubarak from
Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh on bilateral cooperation and
the security in the Red Sea and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak asked him to deliver a message to Saleh, in which
Mubarak expressed appreciation for the "exceptional" ties between
Egypt and Yemen, and to the positions of Yemen and Eritrea on the
arbitration of the Hanish islands in the Red Sea, he said.
</P>
<P>
Disputes of sovereignty over the strategically-important
islands sparked an armed conflict between Yemen and Eritrea in
1995, in which Eritrea captured most of the archipelago.
</P>
<P>
But they later agreed to an arbitration over the issue. The
London-based, five-member International Arbitration Committee
ruled on October 9 that Yemen has sovereignty over most of the
Hanish islands, a decision accepted by the two parties.
</P>
<P>
Ba-Jammal said that Eritrea will hand over the Hanish to Yemen
on Sunday and Eritrean President Isayas Aferworki is expected to
visit Yemen next Wednesday to improve bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a recent peace agreement signed between the
Palestinians and Israel, the Yemeni minister said that "talk about
peace so far remains mere ink on paper." As long as peace "does
not exist on the ground," he said, it would be "premature to
comment on anything," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel signed the interim peace agreement
last week in Washington on Israeli withdrawal from a further 13
percent of the West Bank in exchange for intensified Palestinian
crackdown on Islamic extremes.
</P>
<P>
Ba-Jammal said that he will meet with Egyptian Prime Minister
Kamal El-Ganzouri and other officials to discuss issues including
the formation of a joint bank, a Yemeni company for investment in
Egypt and joint maritime transportation.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni official arrived in Cairo Friday night on a
three-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
