<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Criticized for Stance on Congo (K) Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has criticized
that Rwanda's refusal to acknowledge its military presence in the
war-torn Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) is an obstacle to the
settlement of the crisis there.
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda's stance has created a hurdle...a cease-fire agreement
cannot be reached without first identifying all parties to the
military conflict," local press Sunday quoted Tanzanian Foreign
Minister Jakaya Kikwete as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete, who just returned from a two-day regional meeting in
Zambian capital Lusaka early this week on the DRC crisis, made
the remarks at a press conference in Dar es Salaam Friday.
</P>
<P>
At the Lusaka meeting, Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe declared
publicly that they were supporting DRC President Laurent Kabila's
government army against the rebels, while Uganda alleged that its
troops in the DRC were sent to defend its national security
interests.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda, however, flatly denied its deployment of troops in the
DRC in support of the rebels who launched a revolt on August 2
and now control a large swath of territory in the east of the
third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
The high-level meeting was attended by foreign ministers and
defense ministers from 14 African countries, as well as the
representatives from the Organization of African (OAU), the
Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) and the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba has joined in criticizing
Rwanda, although the meeting finally adopted in principle a draft
cease-fire agreement and a mechanism for implementing and
monitoring the agreement pending further consultations with all
concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba reportedly said that Rwanda is contributing to the
escalating of wars in the DRC and is a stumbling block in the
peace process of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kikwete said the DRC conflicts forced hundreds of
refugees to flow into the Kigoma Region in west Tanzania every
day, causing a headache to local government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
