<HEADLINE> Pakistan Rejects Indian Claims of Attacks at Siachin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Saturday rejected
Indian claims of repulsing Pakistani attacks at Siachin Glacier
and said such statements were aimed at "hiding its own terrorist
acts and vitiating the atmosphere" for the official talks due to
take place next week in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
"It is complete fabrication, nothing of this sort has
happened," Foreign Office spokesman told the weekly press
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"It is baseless," he said of the Indian Defense Ministry's
statement that India foiled two attempts by Pakistani soldiers at
the world's highest glacier to capture a military post in the
week.
</P>
<P>
About the upcoming talks between the defense secretaries of the
two countries on six issues including Siachin, Wuller Barrage and
Sir Creek, the spokesman said "India has taken untenable positions
on all these issues."
</P>
<P>
"On Sir Creek they had accepted the internationally recognized
line but are not accepting it now, their position on Siachin is a
clear violation of Simla Agreement and that on Wuller Barrage is
violative of the Indian Water Basin Accord."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman recalled that India and Pakistan signed an
agreement in 1989 but New Delhi resiled on it. "It is one of the
numerous example of India's resilience on the agreements that it
had signed but only to back out later."
</P>
<P>
He said India's recent claims were aimed at hiding its own
terrorist activities in held Kashmir, "which are on increase."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recently held Islamabad talks between the
Foreign Secretaries of the two countries on Kashmir and
security-related issues, the spokesman said, "we were naturally
disappointed over the lack of progress in these talks."
</P>
<P>
He regretted that New Delhi was unwilling to take steps in
creating a strategic stabilization regime following nuclearization
of the South Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
