<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Opportunities, Challenges Open to HK's IT Industry: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The greatest business
opportunities for the Information Technology (IT) industry lie in
the development of sophisticated Chinese Internet applications and
innovative content, as well as services related to electronic
commerce, Secretary for Information Technology and Broadcasting
K.C. Kwong, said here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the annual conference of the Hong Kong Institution
of Science, Kwong said Hong Kong possessed a competitive edge and
some distinctive comparative advantages not available to many of
its competitors.
</P>
<P>
As a bilingual city, Hong Kong can communicate with and obtain
information from most regions of the digital world where English
is the lingua franca, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong can also use Chinese to promote and develop the
application of Chinese content in the digital world, to co-operate
with other Chinese communities, and to act as the digital
intermediary between China's mainland and other parts of the
world, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Such capability is particularly important in view of the
increasing number of Internet users in Chinese-speaking
communities, and the ever-growing demand for Chinese Internet
applications and content all over the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a cosmopolitan city which accepts different
cultures in the world and its people are quick to assimilate the
latest knowledge and technology. With a free and market-based
economy where a free flow of information is available, the local
community can freely co-operate and make association with any
other place in the world, Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
To assist local industry and business to exploit these
opportunities, the Special Administrative Region (SAR) government
should take the lead in using IT to demonstrate the potentials,
create the necessary environment to facilitate the development of
content and applications, and raise public awareness and
confidence in electronic business.
</P>
<P>
This is precisely the aim of the Electronic Service Delivery
(ESD) scheme, a plan to deliver online government services, he
noted. Through ESD, the public can transact business with
government online and, by means of Internet, interactive
telephone, TV or other electronic means of access, Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government is working on such supporting issues as the
establishment of certification authorities to ensure security of
electronic transactions, and the introduction of a legal framework
to provide necessary backing for electronic commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
