<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Releases Latest Fiscal Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) recorded a fiscal deficit of 42.6
billion HK dollars (5.5 billion U.S. dollars) for the first six
months of the current financial year, the government announced
here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Government expenditure for the six months ended on September
30, 1998 amounted to 115.2 billion HK dollars (14.8 billion U.S.
dollars) and revenue to 72.6 billion HK dollars (9.3 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The SAR government said in a press release Saturday that
"because the accounts are prepared on a cash basis and since the
bulk of the collections from profit tax and salaries tax are
normally received in the second half of the financial year, it is
not unusual, even in good years, to see a substantial deficit in
the first half of the financial year."
</P>
<P>
The fiscal reserves stood at 417.9 billion HK dollars (53.5
billion U.S. dollars) as of September 30, 1998, a decrease of 39.6
billion HK dollars (5.1 billion U.S. dollars) from the level on
March 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The net worth of the Land Fund has increased by 2.97 billion HK
dollars (380 million U.S. dollars) since April 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The SAR released the monthly summary of its financial results
as a further step toward meeting the International Monetary Fund's
Special Data Dissemination Standard. The government said it will
continue to disclose the financial figures on a monthly basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science, Technology Important for HK's Future: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region said here Saturday
that science and technology are important for the future of Hong
Kong although the rewards for the investment in this field may not
be immediately apparent.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the 6th Annual Conference of the
Hong Kong Institution of Science, Tung said that the development
of science and technology as part of Hong Kong's future is
something the government really need to work at though many people
had told him that his initiative to develop science and technology
in Hong Kong will take a long time to realize.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the government is tackling the short-term
economic difficulties as hard as it can. However, the government
should focus the whole community on the long-term future of Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive told the audience of distinguished
scientists and academics that the theme of this year's conference,
with its emphasis on the development of a sustainable economy
through science and technology, is "indeed, a most timely one."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, in his second Policy Address, Tung set out
his firm belief that innovation and technology are important
drivers of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The 21st century will be a knowledge-based world, in which
innovation and technology are essential in adding value,
increasing productivity and enhancing our overall competitiveness,
Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"Innovation and technology also plays a critical role in
enhancing our personal pursuits of excellence, advancing our
industrial development and
improving our quality of life in general," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong must strive to fully equip itself to seize new
opportunities and to compete successfully in the global market as
we enter this new era," Tung stressed.
</P>
<P>
To achieve success in this area requires a dedicated effort and
a commitment to investing in the necessary technological
infrastructure, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that high technology is not necessarily unreachable
and distant, in contrast, it is not remote from people's everyday
life at all.
Innovation and technology are not the prerogative of new
industries, Tung added.
</P>
<P>
In the same way that banking and transportation may be
revolutionized by innovation and technology, so may other
so-called traditional industries, such as textiles, garment,
plastics and metal.
</P>
<P>
These traditionally relatively low-tech industries still have
plenty of opportunities in the global marketplace if they can
increase their added value and productivity through innovation and
application of technology, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Much good work has already been undertaken by the private
sector and this is only right in a free market economy, Tung said.
But the government does recognize that it has to play the role of
a promoter and a facilitator, Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize the need to strengthen Hong Kong's capability to
develop
concepts and innovative ideas into generic technologies for
eventual commercialization by firms," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We also appreciate how difficult it is for our industry,
particularly small and medium-sized enterprises, to invest heavily
in research and development," he added.
</P>
<P>
The government will therefore establish an Applied Science and
Technology Research Institute to support and stimulate mid-stream
research.
</P>
<P>
It will also set up a 5 billion-Hong Kong dollar (641
million-U.S. dollar) Innovation and Technology Fund to finance
projects which will contribute to innovation and the technological
upgrading of our manufacturing and services industries.
</P>
<P>
"We have set out our IT vision to make Hong Kong a leader, not
a follower, in the information world of tomorrow," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to promote the development of an IT infrastructure
which will stimulate the creation of new products," he added.
</P>
<P>
"To demonstrate our commitment, the government will take the
lead in improving our services to the community through an on-line
Government Electronic Services Delivery Scheme," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, which is scheduled to be launched in the year 2000,
will enable the public to access government services on a 24-hour
basis via the Internet and other means of electronic access.
</P>
<P>
"We will also continue our effort to encourage electronic
commerce so that our businesses may strengthen their overall
competitiveness," Tung continued.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to develop Hong Kong into an innovation center
of the region and are committed to a wide range of initiatives to
achieve this purpose," he said.
</P>
<P>
But government effort alone is not enough, Tung said. To
realize the vision, the government needs the support and
contribution of the community, in particular academia and the
business sector, the chief executive said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0108 </DOCNO>
