<HEADLINE> Progress Made in Settlement of DRC Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Some progress has been
made in the efforts to find peace in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC), a senior South African official said in Cape Town
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
President Nelson Mandela's aid Parks Mankahlana said that for
now, the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the United
Nations have been involved in securing a peaceful resolution to
the three-month-old civil war in the DRC,
</P>
<P>
"They are making progress, but it is very slow", he said,
noting that being under discussion were such issues as a
cease-fire, a troops standstill, the withdrawal of foreign
troops, direct negotiations between the warring parties and a
multi-party transitional authority to run the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Mandela's two-day visit to Nigeria starting from
Thursday, Mankahlana said that the South African president had
briefed Nigerian leader Abdulsalam Abubakar on the DRC issue, and
exchanged views on how the situation in the country should be
handled.
</P>
<P>
However, Mankahlana said, there was no attempt to spearhead a
joint South African-Nigerian initiative to find peace in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, 80, has been trying to mediate for peaceful solution
to the DRC crisis which broke out in early August.
</P>
<P>
Since last week, he had met with Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni, Rwandan Deputy President Paul Kagame, Namibian
President Sam Nujoma and DRC rebel leader Wamba dia Wamba.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma is one of the African leaders who sent troops to the
DRC to back DRC President Laurent Kabila, while Museveni and
Kagame were accused by Kabila's government to have been
supporting the DRC rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
