<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Official Leaves for Central Asia for Afghan Consultations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's State Minister for
Foreign Affairs Siddique Khan Kanju left here Saturday for the
Central Asian countries to discuss the evolving situation in
Afghanistan, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Kanju, accompanied by Additional Secretary on Afghanistan
Iftikhar Murshed, will visit Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan,
Tajikstan and Turkmenistan for this purpose, a Foreign Office
spokesman told a weekly news briefing here Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of the current visit is to hold consultations on
further action in implementing the understanding reached at the
six-plus-two meeting at the level of foreign ministers in New York
on September 21 this year," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has consistently tried to coordinate its policies on
Afghanistan closely with all neighboring countries," he said,
adding that Kanju visited Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan and Tajikstan
in August.
</P>
<P>
"The visit takes place in the wake of the highly successful
mission to the region led by the U.N. Secretary General's special
envoy for Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi," he said.
</P>
<P>
The six-plus-two group, namely the six immediate neighbors of
Afghanistan plus the United States and Russia, met in New York on
Thursday and among other things commended the progress made by
Brahimi's mission, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan, which is a leading member of the group has
reiterated its fullest cooperation to the U.N. for the early
restoration of durable peace and stability to Afghanistan," he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
