<HEADLINE> Singapore Unionists Accept Proposed CPF Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The three-day Ordinary
Delegates' Conference of Singapore's National Trades Union
Congress came to a close Saturday after issuing a statement to
accept the proposed 10 percent cut in employers' contribution to
the employees' Central Provident Fund (CPF) account.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the union delegates took the move as
part of the overall cuts in wage and non-wage costs so that
Singapore can regain competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote to the conference Thursday, Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong urged unionists to accept painful but
necessary measures, such as cuts in wages and the CPF, to save
jobs and help the country overcome the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
CPF is a comprehensive social security savings scheme that
takes care of members' retirement, health care, home-ownership and
family protection needs, and enhances their assets. Both the
employer and employee contribute to the employee's CPF account.
</P>
<P>
CPF cuts in employers' contribution is designed to reduce
business costs.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also expressed satisfaction over assurances given
by Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong and Minister for Manpower Lee Boon
Yang on steps that will be put in place to cushion the impact of
the CPF cuts and wage reduction.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they also welcomed Goh Chok Tong's call to
employers to show appreciation for workers' sacrifices and to
reward them when the economy recovers.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also unanimously adopted a resolution, pledging
labor's support for the government "in adopting whatever measures
necessary to counteract the effects of the sharp economic
downturn."
</P>
<P>
The delegates urged employers to come up with an affirmative
response to their move, saying "the ball is now in the employers'
court." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
