<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Meets With Police, Military Chiefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Saturday met with regional police chiefs and military
commanders across the country to brief them on the present
situation in the country and on efforts to make the political
agenda a success.
</P>
<P>
In his explanation to the press after the closed-door meeting,
Minister/State Secretary Akbar Tanjung said Habibie had asked the
police and military chiefs to be patient in facing mounting
demonstrations in the run-up to the planned People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR) special session scheduled for November 10.
</P>
<P>
The rallies were part of democratic process, the head of state
was quoted by Akbar as saying.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, an estimated 10,000 protesters gathered in front
of the MPR/DPR (House of Representatives) complex here, asking
Habibie to immediately hand over power to a transitional
government free of Soeharto-era officials.
</P>
<P>
Former president Soeharto resigned on May 21 amid a deepening
economic crisis, protests and an explosion of rioting in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The protesters reiterated their rejection of next month's
special session of the MPR.
</P>
<P>
Similar protests voicing the same themes took place on
Wednesday in other cities, including Bandung, Semarang and Manado.
No clashes were reported and all of the protests ended peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Akbar told reporters that the political agenda the president
had explained to the regional police and military chiefs included
the planned special session of the MPR, general elections in May
next year and MPR general session to elect new president and vice
president later next year.
</P>
<P>
The special MPR session, from November 10 to 13, is expected to
adopt a timetable for the implementation of general elections and
a general session of MPR next year.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's meeting was also attended by governors of
Indonesia's 27 provinces, Minister of Security and Defense/Armed
Forces Commander General Wiranto, Home Affairs Minister Syarwan
Hamid, Secretary General of the Security and Defense Ministry Lt.
Gen. Soeyono and Armed Forces Chief for Socio-Political Affairs
Lt. Gen. Bambang S. Yudhoyono. 
</P>
</TEXT>
