<HEADLINE> India to Decide on CTBT After Talks With EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 31 (Xinhua) -- India will take a final view
of its nuclear position on negotiations with the United States
only after entering into talks with the European Union (EU) and
Russia in November, a leading Indian daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The annual talks with the EU represented by Austria, United
Kingdom and Germany will cover nuclear non-proliferation and
disarmament, bilateral, security, regional and economic issues,
according to the Pioneer.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the External Affairs Ministry said that British
Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs Derek
Fatchel and Austrian Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs Binita
Ferrero-Waldner are scheduled to arrive in New Delhi on November
13 and a Russian deputy atomic energy minister will visit India on
November 6.
</P>
<P>
Though the name of the German minister in the EU delegation is
yet to be confirmed, it is reportedly said to be the first
high-level German official to visit India after Chancellor Gerhard
Schroder assumed office in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
The last annual EU-India Ministerial Troika meeting was held in
Luxembourg in September 1997
</P>
<P>
As a combined body, the EU is India's largest trading partner
with 26 percent of its exports and 30 percent of its imports.
</P>
<P>
After India's nuclear tests last May, the EU had asked New
Delhi to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
There has been no breakthrough in talks between India and the
United States which began in June this year with the U.S.
insisting on India's signing of the CTBT and giving up its nuclear
development programs.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said that talks between India and the EU would
provide the necessary maneuvering space to New Delhi for its
subsequent three-day expert-level talks with Washington.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the Indian government would not take its
final position on negotiations with the U.S. on the CTBT, dual-use
technologies and the so-called "nuclear restraint regime" before
it entering into talks with the EU and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
