<HEADLINE> AIDS Program Launched in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda AIDS Commission
(UAC) has launched a new HIV/AIDS program for the years 1997-2000
with a budgetary estimate of 36 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The program named "Country Cooperation Framework-5" seeks to
alert Ugandans about the dangers of AIDS and its implications in
relation to poverty, the New Vision daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It will be funded by the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) and will empower infected and the unprivileged people such
as widows and orphans with income generating projects.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony in Kampala Friday, UAC
Director-General Omwony Ojwok said that the new program will
mostly address the problems concerning HIV/AIDS, gender and
environment.
</P>
<P>
This program is a follow-up of the 1992-1996 UNDP Fourth
Country Program funded at a cost of 10 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The increasing number of AIDS affected people in the whole
country deserves continued poverty eradication assistance to
improve their welfare in the long run, the UAC boss asserted.
</P>
<P>
One-tenth of Uganda's population of more than 23 million are
estimated to be HIV-positive and some 500,000 Ugandans have died
of the epidemic since the first case was reported in the country
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Poverty has been held for being partially responsible for the
high infection rate. At present, some reports said half of the
population are living under the poverty line in the east African
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
