<HEADLINE> EU's Partial Removal of Sanctions on Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar lauded the gesture of the European Union (EU)
for partially lifting its sanctions imposed on Nigeria for human
rights violation and lack of democracy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the 21st summit of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) Friday in capital
Abuja, Abubakar said that with the action, the EU had
demonstrated its recognition of the development since the new
administration came into office in June.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader pledged that the west African country
would continue on the path of reconciliation, The Guardian
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The EU Friday decided to ease diplomatic and sporting
sanctions, but those on military cooperation, sales of arms,
ammunition and military equipment to Nigeria will remain in force
until democratic rule is restored in the most populous African
country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman of the United States State Department
James Rubin announced Friday that his government had set aside
the order restricting the entry of certain category of Nigerians
into the U.S.
</P>
<P>
He said that the order was no longer necessary because of the
recent development in the country since new head of state
Abubakar assumed office on June 8.
</P>
<P>
The order, issued on December 10, 1993, restricted the entry
into U.S. of persons who formulate, implement or benefit from
policies that impede Nigeria's transition program and immediate
family members of such persons.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the British Commonwealth lifted the
sanction imposed on Nigeria in 1995, but decided to keep
Nigeria's membership suspended until Abubakar fulfilled his
promise of handing over to a democratically elected civilian
regime.
</P>
<P>
The EU, British Commonwealth and United States imposed limited
sanctions on Nigeria following the killing of Ken Saro-Wiwa and
eight Ogoni activists in November, 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
