<HEADLINE> FUNCINPEC Reaffirms its Power Sharing Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 31 (Xinhua) -- FUNCINEC said it did not
propose a co-chairmanship of the National Assembly nor would the
party agree to take such a creative but powerless position,
blaming the present deadlock on the ruling Cambodian People's
Party (CPP).
</P>
<P>
FUNCINPEC made the statement in a news release issued Saturday.
It is also the response to CPP President Chea Sim's statement
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A CPP document Wednesday said the party was willing to make
concessions to the opposition and restart negotiations. The party
did not win enough seats in July's election to form a government
alone.
</P>
<P>
But FUNCINPEC said, "CPP's concessions are no concessions ...
should the CPP want to truly resolve the present deadlock,
solutions would be found."
</P>
<P>
FUNCINPEC's news release stressed that "as the party has
learned well that co-chairing anything with the CPP means
surrendering full power to them. Furthermore, such proposal is
unconstitutional."
</P>
<P>
"FUNCINPEC proposed that the chairman, first vice-chairman and
second vice-chairman positions be offered respectively to
FUNCINPEC, CPP and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP), and the nine
commissions be chaired under the formula of four-four-one," it
insisted.
</P>
<P>
It claimed, "the CPP's offer to share four out of the nine
Parliamentarian Commissions with FUNCINPEC, leaving the SRP no
role in the commissions is unacceptable and against national
reconciliation."
</P>
<P>
FUNCINPEC said it believed that discussions on the sharing of
power should not be addressed until the three winning parties
agree on a common political agenda for the long term development
of the nation. Such agenda needs to give priority to the issues
affecting the lives of all Cambodians and the future of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
Prince Ranariddh and other party members have been in Bangkok
for more than a month, claiming it is not safe for them to return.
</P>
<P>
The three parties have held one summit and three working group
meetings but failed to make much progress. 
</P>
