<HEADLINE> Pak Revenue Collection 13 Billion Rupees Short of Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's revenue collection
in the first four months of the 1998-99 fiscal year starting from
July 1 was 13 billion rupees (46 rupees equal one dollar) short of
the budgetary target.
</P>
<P>
The revenue collection during the four months stood at 83
billion rupees against the target of 96 billion rupees, according
to the Central Board of Revenue.
</P>
<P>
The total revenue target for the financial year set by the
government is 354 billion rupees.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that revenue of 24 billion rupees had been
collected during the outgoing month of October against the target
of 29 billion rupees, showing a shortfall of five billion rupees.
</P>
<P>
However, official sources said that the anticipated shortfall
during the whole fiscal year is likely to be less than 18 billion
rupees against a shortfall of 30 billion rupees in the previous
fiscal year of 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Describing the existing economic crisis facing the country as a
major factor towards expected shortfall in the revenue collection,
the sources said fall in customs duty and decline in the
collection of sales tax on import-related goods are an outcome of
declining trend in imports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, economic analysts observed that the current style of
management of balance of payment might not work and there would be
lesser amount of export earnings, further aggravating the balance
of payment position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
