<HEADLINE> West Provides $46 Million for Mozambique's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The donors from the United
States and Europe have agreed to provide 46 million U.S. Dollars
as start-up capital for a agricultural program in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Carlos de Rosario, Mozambican Minister of Agriculture and
Fishery, said here Friday that the Western donors had reached an
agreement with his government on the Agricultural Program of
Public Investment in Mozambique after several days of talks.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's Noticias newspaper quoted the minister as saying
that the 202-million-U.S. Dollar program will be launched in 1999
and completed within five years.
</P>
<P>
Rosario noted that the international donors have shown their
confidence in the Mozambican government by providing funds for
the agricultural investment program.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Mozambican officials at various levels to work
hard and improve efficiency in a bid to carry out the program.
</P>
<P>
All parties concerned should build up confidence in each other
and hold constant dialogs, the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Vice Minister of Agriculture and Fishery Isidora
Fastudo also said that the donors have promised more funds than
expected.
</P>
<P>
"We expected that the program will need 35 million to 36
million U.S. Dollars in 1999," said Fastudo.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the Western donors made it clear that the
interests of the farmers in the poor southern African countries
should be protected by a land act.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister added that the Mozambican government is
intensifying its efforts to ensure that a land act could be
approved in the parliament before the end of November this year.
</P>
