<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Govts Challenged to Invest in Knowledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 31 (Xinhua) -- John Mugabe, chief of the
Nairobi-based African Center for Technology Studies (ACTS), has
urged African governments to invest in the generation and use of
knowledge and get their people trained locally.
</P>
<P>
Africa's problems could only be solved through the acquisition
of appropriate knowledge in correspondence to Africa's needs, he
was quoted by Saturday's Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We need to initiate and sustain African institutions to
create knowledge appropriate to Africa," he said when briefing
Kenya-based ambassadors from 12 African countries.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also attributed the continent's troubles to
"deliberate" failure by its people to use knowledge based on
African conditions.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that Africans do not appreciate indigenous
institutions. Instead, they neglect or abandon them in favor of
external ones."
</P>
<P>
He said Africa spends a lot of money to train people in Europe
and America, but that the knowledge they acquired was irrelevant
to the African market needs.
</P>
<P>
Envoys from Ethiopia, Zambia, Zimbabwe, Nigeria, Malawi, South
Africa, Morocco, Mozambique, Algeria, Rwanda, Burundi and
Tanzania attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
ACTS is an inter-governmental policy institution with four
African countries as members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
