<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks in Nairobi Bourse Hit New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The Nairobi Stock Exchange
(NSE) 20-share index fell to a new low Friday in four and
half years, despite a continued slide in domestic interest rates,
local media reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The NSE-20 index fell 5.67 points or 0.21 percent to close at
2,733.68, its lowest point since January 14, 1994, the exchange
said.
</P>
<P>
The index was down 37.92 points or 1.37 percent in the last
week.
</P>
<P>
Some brokers said a recovery was overdue after a dramatic
slide in treasury bill rates in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Others said the stagnant Kenyan economy, poor profits
forecasts and a negative international environment might
overshadow the market for a little while longer.
</P>
<P>
"Because liquidity is so low, it won't take a great deal of
institutional money to switch from short-term debt into equities
to turn the market round," said Rick Ashley, chief of Kestrel
Capital (East Africa), one of the major dealers.
</P>
<P>
Kestrel has been recommending its clients take a closer look
at the Kenya equity market after a fall in benchmark treasury
bill yields that has brought the 91-day rate to 19.27 percent
this week from around 27 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Ashley pointed out that dividend yields of between 12 and 15
percent on many blue chip stocks represented good value, and said
government efforts to balance its budget implied that interest
rates could stay low.
</P>
<P>
Other brokers said the market was hampered by the poor
economic environment and overseas selling of stocks.
</P>
<P>
"From foreigners, we are seeing more selling than buying
orders -- in fact we aren't seeing many buying orders," said
Amish Gupta at Shah, Munge and Partners, "They are out primarily
because of the emerging markets crisis around the world."
</P>
<P>
NSE data shows that foreigners were net sellers of Kenyan
stocks to the tune of 119.7 million Shillings (two million U.S.
Dollars) in September, for the first time since March 1996.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was posted at 8.5 million Shillings on 225,000 shares
Friday down from 13.2 million Shillings on 254,000 shares
Thursday, said the NSE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
