<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Down-Size Troops in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The South African
National Defense Force (SANDF) is to withdraw 1,400 of its 3,500
combat troops from Lesotho next week, according to a SANDF
general.
</P>
<P>
SANDF chief General Siphiwe Nyanda said Friday that 600 with
lightly armed peacekeepers will be sent in, bringing the number
of South African soldiers in Lesotho to 2,700.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports Saturday quoted the general as saying that
the 600 troops will arrive Monday and the 1,400 troops will leave
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 600 new troops would work with the Lesotho police to trace
illegal weapons, while the remaining 2,100 would keep peace in
the mountains where criminals armed with illegal weapons were
reported to be operating.
</P>
<P>
The scale-down has clearly been allowed by the reduction in
tension following the agreement reached by the Lesotho government
and the opposition parties on a multi-party transitional
authority to ensure free and fair elections in no more than 18
months.
</P>
<P>
A dispute between the Lesotho government and the opposition
over the May 23 general election boiled up to a major political
crisis in September, leading to the military intervention of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
On September 22, 600 South African troops entered Lesotho to
help restore order in its capital of Maseru, followed by 200
Botswanan soldiers later that day.
</P>
<P>
The SADC forces encountered unexpectedly fierce resistance
from mutinous Lesotho soldiers, and South Africa was forced to
deploy more troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0136 </DOCNO>
