<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 07:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Vows to Smash Attempts to Sabotage Interim Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) cabinet has approved the land-for-peace deal newly
signed with Israel, vowing to crack down on those attempting to
sabotage "the national achievement" by violence.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Saturday that the accord was passed by a
large majority in a weekly cabinet meeting held Friday night in
the West Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after the meeting warned that any attempt to
destroy the "national achievement" accomplished after two years of
exhausted effort will not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
PNA Presidential Secretary-General Tayeb Abdul Rahim said the
PNA did not object to statements issued by Islamic militant group
Hamas rejecting the interim agreement, but it would confront any
attempt to derail the peace process by force.
</P>
<P>
He also said Hamas would be held responsible for a suicide car
bombing Thursday in Gaza which killed the attacker and an Israeli
soldier, and injured five people.
</P>
<P>
The PNA responded quickly and harshly to the attack. Scores of
Hamas activists, including some prominent members, have been
arrested by Palestinian security forces in the wake of the car
bombing.
</P>
<P>
And in an unprecedented move, the PNA has placed Hamas
spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin under house arrest since
Thursday. He was not allowed out for prayers Friday and reports
said Palestinian security forces have searched his house in Gaza,
confiscated documents and cut off the telephone line.
</P>
<P>
Under the interim agreement signed by Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the White House last week, the PNA
will take tougher measures to fight terrorism while Israel hands
over more West Bank land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
U.S. National Security Adviser Sandy Berger was quoted by
Israel Radio as hailing the PNA measures in the past two days as a
"quite vigorous" effort against terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
