<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buildings Demolished to Improve Capital's Looks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital of Beijing
has moved to improve its appearance for the celebration of the
50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic in
October next year.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 buildings totaling 800,000 square meters have
been demolished since early this year. These buildings, mostly
roughly made sheds or makeshift housing, clogged the streets and
green areas and tarnished the looks of the capital.
</P>
<P>
In the Chongwen District, city inspectors closed a ten-year-old
unauthorized bird market which had occupied 1,600 square meters of
sidewalk. One street in the Haidian District, which used to be
notorious for security problems, had 3,700 square meters of space
cleared up and some vendors without licenses were forced to go.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has also decided to give a major
facelift to Tiananmen Square in the heart of Beijing by planting
more flowers and greenery on both sides of Chang'an
Boulevard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Company to Produce Notebook Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 31 (Xinhua) -- A notebook computer venture
jointly funded by Qinghua Unisplendor Co. and the Hainan Cable
Plant is scheduled to enter operations by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The new venture, established with an initial investment of 30
million yuan (3.62 million US dollars), will produce 15,000
notebook computers in its first year of operations.
</P>
<P>
The production capacity will grow to 80,000 computers annually
by the third year and projections call for the annual out put
value to hit one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Most computers produced during the initial period will be
assembled with imported parts and researchers from Qinghua
University will work to develop new domestic products.
</P>
<P>
The venture is located in the city of Wenchang in Hainan
Province, China's southernmost island province.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has placed priority on the development of its
information industry and introduced a series of preferential
policies to attract reputable companies in the sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
