<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF to Intensify Support for Children in Great </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) will intensify its support for the children in the
Great Lakes region, putting more emphasis on the war-torn
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
in Harare Friday, UNICEF's Regional Representative for East and
Southern Africa Urban Johnsson said there is now greater need for
support from the organization because the war has left many
children traumatized and suffering.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF is part of the U.N. agencies negotiating with the
rebels who control most of the eastern part of the DRC to
facilitate the delivery of food supplies to the affected areas,
the daily Herald reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Johnsson sought advice from President Mugabe on how his
organization could help the children in the Great Lakes region,
the DRC in particular.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean president emphasized the need for the UNICEF to
continuously remind the world leaders that in any war, children
are the most affected and traumatized.
</P>
<P>
There are no losers or winners in a war because wars bring
tragedy, said Mugabe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
