<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wellington Airport Receives More Passengers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Passenger numbers at New
Zealand's Wellington International Airport increased to 3.5
million in the year to June 30 from 3.34 million in the previous
year, the Evening Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted the annual report of the
airport company as saying that domestic passenger numbers
increased from 2.99 million last year to 3.11 million this year.
Meanwhile, international passenger numbers rose from 354,000 to
388,000.
</P>
<P>
This compares to a 3.3 percent fall in the year to June 30 in
international passenger number at Auckland International Airport,
the biggest airport in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Denis Thom of the Wellington airport company was
quoted as saying that Wellington International Airport has strong
domestic traffic, made up of mainly business travelers and some
leisure travelers. The airport also caters for the trans-Tasman
routes and Pacific islands. Not having long-haul flights to Asia
and beyond means the company is not affected by the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the number of international passengers is
largely due to airlines increasing their flights to Australia,
particularly in the past year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 66 percent shareholding in Wellington International
Airport, which had been owned by the New Zealand Government, was
sold to Infratil New Zealand in August. Infratil NZ is jointly
owned by New Zealand Airports, a consortium led by Infratil;
British investment groups Alliance Life Common Fund; and Foreign
and Colonial Special Utilities Investment Trust.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 34 percent stake in the airport is still owned by
the Wellington City Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
