<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Confidence in New Zealand Slips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 31 (Xinhua) -- Business confidence in New
Zealand
has slipped again and a deteriorating world economy can take much
of the
blame, the New Zealand Press Association (NZPA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The NZPA quoted the latest survey by the National Bank of New
Zealand
as saying that 36 percent of firms questioned in the bank's
October
business confidence survey expect general business conditions to
improve
over the next year, with 27 percent expecting business conditions
to
worsen, a margin of nine percentage points.
</P>
<P>
But in September, that margin was 14 percentage points and just
two
months ago, the percentage of optimistic firms exceeded that of
pessimistic ones by 40 points.
</P>
<P>
National Bank's chief economist Brendan O'Donovan was quoted as

saying that businesses were weighing the effects of easier
domestic
monetary policy and a deteriorating international environment.
"International uncertainty is proving heavier," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The international environment looks shakier by the day and it
is no
exaggeration to say that it is in its most vulnerable state in 50

years," O'Donovan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
