<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Pharmaceutical Industry Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 31 (Xinhua) -- The pharmaceutical industry in
Bangladesh is thriving with local companies producing about 95
percent of the required drugs in the country, according to the
latest issue of the weekend magazine Daily Star.
</P>
<P>
The industry, with a growth rate of 12 to 15 percent a year,
has become something the Bangladeshi people can be proud of, the
magazine said, adding that there are now 208 licensed drug
manufacturers in the country, with a total employment of 65,000
people.
</P>
<P>
Since 1982 when the Drug Policy was initiated, the industry has
grown by almost eight times as local companies are flourishing in
the country, it observed.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the 1980s, the pharmaceutical sector in the country
had been dominated by several multinational companies. In 1982,
the multinational companies dominated 52 percent market share, but
by 1996 it dwindled to a meager 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
The magazine also attributed the rapid growth of the sector to
such factors as quality of products, availability of more kinds of
drugs and affordable price.
</P>
<P>
The pharmaceutical industry sector can not only meet 95 percent
of local required drugs but also export its products to more than
20 countries in Asia, Africa, Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
Although the total export earnings are still only about 250
million taka (5.15 million U.S. dollars), the possibilities are
enormous, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The government departments concerned have been urged to make
some amendments to the existing drug policy and introduce modern
technologies to maintain the quality of products and at the same
time open the sector wider to foreign investors, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
