<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Abortion Clinics Receive Anthrax Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- A sudden anthrax threat on
Friday to four U.S. abortion clinics resulted in the sending of
at least 33 people to hospitals, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The four clinics in three U.S. states received letters Friday
claiming to contain deadly anthrax bacillus, which led to the
evacuation of an Indianapolis clinic.
</P>
<P>
Clinics in New Albany, Louisville, Kentucky, and Knoxville,
Tennessee, also received similar letters, federal officials were
quoted as saying by the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Employees and patients at the Indianapolis Planned Parenthood
clinic were stripped and scrubbed down by emergency crews after
one of them opened a small powder-filled letter.
</P>
<P>
A postal carrier, two police officers and 28 other people were
treated in Indianapolis. Officials said it was unclear whether the
letter actually contained anthrax bacillus, a strain of bacteria
that can be used as a biological weapon.
</P>
<P>
None of those treated in Indianapolis complained of any
symptoms, but authorities took them to a hospital after they were
decontaminated in a tent put up near the clinic. They were given
antibiotics as a preventive measure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
