<HEADLINE> Macedonian PM: NATO Deployment Has Legal Basis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The deployment of NATO force in
Macedonia has its legal basis, Macedonian Prime Minister Branko
Crvenkovski said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to BBC on the possibility of NATO deployment to
replace the United Nations Preventive Deployment Force (UNPREDEP),
the prime minister said the UNPREDEP's mission in his country is
only temporary.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that there could be an early solution to the
current crisis in Kosovo saying if the crisis there worsens,
Macedonia will be the first to be affected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, US envoy to the Balkan region Richard Holbrooke said
a rapid NATO deployment will be staged once the Macedonian
government agrees.
</P>
<P>
The primary role of the NATO force in Macedonia will be to
extract members of the verification force from Kosovo in case of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on October 19, the Macedonian government granted NATO
the right to use its airports for monitoring flight over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia used to be part of the Yugoslav federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
