<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Help African Countries Improve Aviation Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced
on Friday that it has invited eight African nations to participate
in an aviation safety program to raise their flying standards and
promote trade.
</P>
<P>
"Safe air travel and secure airports are prerequisites for
Africa's integration into the global economy for increasing trade,
attracting investment, growing a tourism industry and weaving
together a modern society," U.S. Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Slater said the eight nations are Angola, Cameroon, Cape Verde,
Ivory Coast, Kenya, Mali, Tanzania and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The United States will send teams next year to review the
aviation needs of these countries and to work out plans for
improving their aviation infrastructure, he said.
</P>
<P>
Improved aviation, Slater said, would push the U.S. trade with
Africa, which presently accounts for only one percent of U.S.
trade.
</P>
<P>
The so-called safe skies program was established in April by
U.S. President Bill Clinton. It is one of several U.S. aviation
initiatives in Africa, aimed at increasing travel and trade
between the United States and Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
