<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Urges Asia Not Turn to Protectionism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Friday urged nations hit by the Asian financial
crisis not to turn to the protectionism in search for economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the call when delivering a speech at the 10th
annual George Marshall lecture at Hudson Bay School in the
Northwestern state of Washington.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright also called on international financial
institutions to help countries do more to cope with social
hardships caused by the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The institutions "must do more to help countries cope with the
social hardships created by the current crisis and develop better
strategies for preventing future ones," she said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary is on a two-day speaking tour of the West Coast
ahead of the meetings of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) forum in Kuala Lumpur next month. She will accompany
President Bill Clinton to the forum.
</P>
<P>
She praised the vision of expanded trade and free markets
embodied in the Marshall plan, initiated by the U.S. to assist
European countries after the World War II. The plan has helped
spread prosperity around the world, she said.
</P>
<P>
This is especially true in the American Northwest "where the
economy is an export powerhouse and the boom in trade with Asia
has provided good jobs in everything from computers to shipping to
agriculture," she noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the financial crisis that began in Southeast Asia,
spread to Russia and now threatens the Western hemisphere is
posing a challenge to these policies, she said.
</P>
<P>
"There remains a risk that leaders in some nations will panic
and turn to the false gods of protectionism or the impossible goal
of isolation in today's global economy," she said.
</P>
<P>
Praising Thailand, Brazil and South Korea for responding to the
crisis with a deeper commitment to democracy, fighting corruption
and economic reform, Albright urged countries to undertake sounder
and more transparent financial practices.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration is "determined to get the prosperity
train back on track" and that is why Clinton put forward a plan to
restore growth and contain the financial crisis, said Albright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
