<HEADLINE> Japan Grants Guatemala Loan, Donation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Japan Friday granted
Guatemala a loan and a donation totaling 57.2 million
U.S. dollars for the development of infrastructure in the
country's civil war-devastated areas.
</P>
<P>
A protocol was signed in Guatemala City Friday by Guatemalan
Foreign Minister Eduardo Stein and Japanese Ambassador to
Guatemala Hisoto Murayama.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala will receive a 48.9 million dollar Japanese loan
repayable in 30 years, and a donation of almost 8.3 million
dollars, according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used for the construction, rehabilitation, and
maintenance of rural roads in the north and west of the country,
the worst-hit area by the 35-year civil war. The World Bank will
also provide funds for the area's development.
</P>
<P>
The donation will be used for health care and the promotion of
the historical and archeological heritage in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
