<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Appoints Superintendents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 31 (Xinhua) -- For the first time, China's
Supreme People's Court appointed 10 prestigious judges as
superintendents to supervise the work of local curts and
investigate cases of judicial corruption, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
The English-language newspaper quoted Xiao Yang, president of
the supreme court, as saying that the appointment is aimed at
"propelling the the development of the trial system in China and
safeguarding judicial justice."
</P>
<P>
The paper said that three of the appointees are retired
presidents of local higher people's courts and the rest are
members of the Supreme People's Court Judicial Committee or heads
of the court's departments. Zhu Mingshan, vice-president of the
supreme court, will head the 10 superintendents.
</P>
<P>
The superintendents will be responsible for offering advice in
handling major, difficult or misjudged cases. They are also
authorized to investigate major issues concerning judicial
corruption in the courts, as well as cases involving parties from
different jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
They are required to forward reports and suggestions to the
supreme court based on their investigations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
