<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakia's New Government Takes Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia's new coalition
government took office Friday with Mikulas Dzurinda as Prime
Minister.
</P>
<P>
The new government, composed of a prime minister, four deputy
prime ministers and 15 ministers, was sworn in by Jozef Migas, who
was elected parliament chairman Thursday and is acting head of
state in the absence of a president.
</P>
<P>
Dzurinda, leader of the Slovak Democratic Coalition (SDK),
became prime minister after a four-party opposition coalition
garnered some 60 percent of votes in the September 25-26
parliamentary elections, ousting former Prime Minister Vladimir
Meciar and his Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS).
</P>
<P>
The opposition coalition holds 93 seats in the 150-seat
single-chamber parliament while Meciar's party only holds 43
seats, way below the required number of seats for a majority in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The four coalition parties then drove a hard bargain over the
allocation of government posts, and reached agreement Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
Under the cabinet deal, Dzurinda's SDK, the largest ruling
party, has nine government posts, against six for the Party of the
Democratic Left (SDL), three for the Hungarian Coalition Party
(SMK), and two for the Party of Civic Understanding (SOP).
</P>
<P>
Dzurinda, 42, was born in an east Slovakia town, Spis. He once
worked with Slovak railway management bureau and was briefly
Minister of Transportation in 1994. He came to chair the SDK in
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
