<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Laundering in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Money laundered through the
Latin American financial system comes mostly from illegal traffic
in drugs and arms, Latin American Banks Federation Consultant
Jaime Ospina said Friday in Santo Domingo.
</P>
<P>
Ospina was in the capital city of the Dominican Republic to
attend the 13th Latin American Bank Security Congress, which
started Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ospina said that drug traffickers transferred some 400 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997 in the global financial system.
</P>
<P>
Ospina said money laundering and the activities of the
financial entities that promote it damage the climate of security,
corrupt employees and bank practices, and undermine control
schemes.
</P>
<P>
He added that preventive measures must be taken inside the
financial entities since "organized crime has been globalized
ahead of industries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
