<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Large Brazilian State Firms to Reduce Budgets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Two Brazilian large
state-owned energy enterprises will reduce their budgets by 1.8
billion reals (1.512 billion U.S. dollars) under a government's
fiscal adjustment, a senior official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The budget cut for Petrobras will be 980 million dollars, and
532 million dollars in Electrobras, Mines and Energy Minister
Raimundo Britto said.
</P>
<P>
The two firms budget cuts were part of a fiscal adjustment
program announced this week by the government, which expects to
save 23.5 billion dollars next year, of which 7.31 billion dollars
will come out of the official spending reduction.
</P>
<P>
The adjustment goal is to balance the country's public accounts
through primary surpluses of 2.6 percent of the Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) in 1999, 2.8 percent in 2000, and 3.0 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 national budget that will be modified in the next week
allocated 37.328 billion dollars for Petrobras, and 8.137 billion
for Electrobras.
</P>
<P>
Britto said the budget cuts will not affect the resources
tagged for projects considered crucial in the two companies.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the Angra II nuclear plant, in the Rio de
Janeiro littoral, and the Brazil-Bolivia gas pipeline are among
the projects which will not be affected by the budget cuts, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
