<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Allocation for Science Declines in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian budget allocation
for science represented only 0.16 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) this year compared to 0.17 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Professor Ivan Matev, chairman of the Union of Bulgarian
Scientists (UBS), said Friday in his report to the seventh
congress of UBS that only 1 percent of the higher schools' budgets
is used for scientific research.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial information shows that 13 percent of the funds
invested in scientific studies have come from the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Matev said that in 1995, 57 percent of the funds for scientific
studies went for wages, 38.1 percent for operating expenses and
4.9 percent for investment and renovation of equipment.
</P>
<P>
The total number of Bulgarian scientists in various fields
reached 25,871 in 1997, including 1,428 professors, 4,056
associate professors and 10,104 doctors or doctoral candidates of
science, Matev said.
</P>
<P>
The seventh congress of the Union of Bulgarian Scientists will
discuss a draft on reform in Bulgarian science. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
