<HEADLINE> Nazi Nada Sakic to Be Extradited to Croatia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Nada Sakic, head of the
Jasenovac concentration camp feminine area, will be extradited to
Croatia to be tried there for crimes she committed during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed Friday here by Victor Ramos, president of
the National Institute Against Discrimination, Racism, and
Xenophobia, of Argentina. He said Sakic will leave Sunday for
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Nada Sakic is the wife of Dinko Sakic, commander of the
Jasenovac concentration camp, who was extradited last June to
Croatia to be tried for Nazi crimes committed there during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
Both were detained in their homes in the Argentine city of
Santa Teresita, where they resided since the end of World War II
to escape the sentence dictated against them by the former
Yugoslavia government.
</P>
<P>
The Jasenovac concentration camp is near the city of the same
name, some 62.5 miles southeast of Zagreb, in a territory that now
is part of Croatia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
