<HEADLINE> 96,000 Filipino Workers in Malaysia Face Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 31 (Xinhua) -- About 96,000 illegal Filipino
workers in Malaysia are facing arrests and deportation for
ignoring that country's amnesty program.
</P>
<P>
The official Philippine Journal newspaper reported Saturday
that the two-month amnesty granted by the Malaysian government is
expiring Saturday, but as of Friday less than 2 percent of 96,803
illegal Filipino migrants had voluntarily availed of the amnesty
which runs from August 31 to October 31.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Philippine Department of Foreign Affairs
said Friday that the Malaysian government has not yet seriously
indicated that it would conduct a massive roundup and deportation
of illegal foreign workers when the deadline expires Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"But the more prudent course of action would be to anticipate
for the worst case scenario," said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the Philippine government has
allocated 85,000 U.S. dollars as seafare repatriation expense for
the illegal Filipino workers for one month only. 
</P>
