<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Train 2,200 Volleyball Coaches by 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The chairman of Tanzania Amateur Volleyball Association
(TAVA), Patrick Sombe, said here Friday that TAVA has already
trained more than 300 coaches to make volleyball become a popular
sport second to football in the country.
</P>
<P>
Opening an eight-day basic volleyball coaching course for Dar
es Salaam Region primary school teachers, Sombe said TAVA this
year has held eight courses in regions of Iringa, Mbeya, Tanga,
Dar es Salaam and Dodoma and will hold courses in Arusha and
Kilimanjaro regions.
</P>
<P>
The association is also planning extra courses in Dar es
Salaam region, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the International Volleyball Federation (FIVB) has
promised to lend support to TAVA in training coaches for primary
and secondary school students.
</P>
<P>
Sombe also said that trainees in the courses who performs well
will have the opportunity to receive further training in Zambia
and Sudan, where FIVB has two regional volleyball coaching
schools.
</P>
<P>
The chairman appealed to the Ministry of Education and Culture
to have a fresh look at the curricula of primary and secondary
schools and colleges and give more classes for sports.
</P>
<P>
He said volleyball is a sport which demands no huge amount of
money in buying the required equipment and there is no
justification for schools failing to carry out the training
programs for it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
