<HEADLINE> Italian Foreign Minister Urges Calm on Pinochet Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini on Friday called for the keeping of patience in dealing with
the case of former Chilean president, Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of a conference on international aid here,
Dini said,"We must, first of all, await the response" of the House
of Lords on the British High Court which ruled Wednesday that
Pinochet was entitled to immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
However, Pinochet, 82 and senator-for-life, could not leave
Britain until prosecutors appealed the ruling to a five-judge
tribunal in the House of Lords, which will hear the case next week.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, who had an operation for a lumbar disc hernia in
London, was detained by British police on October 16 at a request
of Spanish judge Baltasar Garzon, who investigated human rights
violations in Chile during Pinochet's rule from 1973 to early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 2,000 people were killed for
political reasons in Chile between 1973 and 1978 while another
1,100 disappeared and remained missing.
</P>
<P>
Dine said that his nation strongly condemned General Augusto
Pinochet's dictatorial regime in Chile.
</P>
<P>
But the case should be handled "with great calm and without
excessive emotion," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Italian foreign minister also expressed his government's
full support to the democratic government of Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
