<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Begins Air Verification Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 30 (Xinhua) -- A group of American U-2 spy planes
on Friday began reconnaissance flights over Kosovo to monitor the
withdrawal of Serbian forces from the mostly Albanian region in
line with the U.N. demands.
</P>
<P>
The jets flew at an altitude of 20 thousand feet, to avoid any
anti-aircraft fire, but were able to photograph the ground in
minute details through the electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
The U-2 squadron, deployed at the NATO (North Atlantic Treaty
Organization) Aviano base in Italy, is composed of four pilots
backed up by over 40 technicians under the command of
Lt. Col. Bruce Jenneman.
</P>
<P>
"These boys fly once every three days because of the
particularly stressful nature of their task," Jenneman told
reporters here, adding that pilot must wear special suits similar
to the ones astronauts use because of the high altitude they are
flying.
</P>
<P>
NATO ordered the start of the surveillance mission over Kosovo
earlier Friday to complement the work of verifiers on the ground
from the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements reached with NATO earlier this month, the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia agreed to the air and ground
verification of its compliance with the U.N. resolution demanding
the pull-out of Serb forces, a return of refugees and the start of
autonomy talks with the ethnic majority in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
