<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Paralyzed Gymnast Leaves U.S. Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I shall never give in," said the 17-year-old as she left the
Mount Sinai-New York University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
"Christopher Reeve said to me that one day we would all stand
up and walk again. I believe this day will come," added Sang, who
injured her spinal cord in July and still has no feeling from her
mid-chest down.
</P>
<P>
"I feel sad that I'm paralyzed and can't take care of myself
like normal people," Sang said. "But I don't want to lose the
confidence that I'll stand up again."
</P>
<P>
Dr. Kristjan Ragnarsson, an expert on spinal cord injuries who
has worked closely with the teen-ager, said the gymnast has made
excellent progress with increased muscle strength at her
shoulders, elbows and wrists.
</P>
<P>
In a moving farewell at the hospital, Sang raised her arms and
waved good-bye with obvious difficulty. Her immediate plans are
to continue rehabilitation and learn English.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vaulting queen was a member of the Chinese
national team. She injured during the warm-up before the vaulting
competition on July 21 when she fell head first in a vaulting
jump.
</P>
<P>
Sang can write her name, feed herself and brush her teeth.
</P>
<P>
"I want to say thank you to Dr. Ragnarsson and Mount Sinai,"
Sang said. "They have given me the best therapies and medical
care. They have even trained my mother so that she is able to
take care of me at home."
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ragnarsson called Sang "an inspiration for other patients
and for the staff that worked with her." He said that she had not
missed a day of her strenuous rehabilitation program and remained
highly motivated.
</P>
<P>
Sang's mother will remain with her in New York, while her
father returns home to China. The Goodwill Games Organizing
Committee has covered all the medical cost for the Chinese
gymnast. Sang has not decided when she will return to China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
