<HEADLINE> WBC to Push for Inclusion of Boxing in Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This was one of the resolutions adopted at the WBC's annual
convention in Johannesburg which ended on Friday, South African
state television reported.
</P>
<P>
If accepted, boxing would be the latest official sporting code
of the Olympics. Other codes include basketball, soccer and
tennis.
</P>
<P>
The world boxing sanctioning body also approved the acceptance
of women boxing, a junior tournament for boxers under 22 and the
staging of a world cup of boxing. It also agreed that red cards
would be used to stop the fight.
</P>
<P>
WBC president Jose Sulaiman said the convention was one of the
important milestones in the history of the organization.
</P>
<P>
"We approved so many different things in this convention that
everybody says it was one of the best in history," Sulaiman said.
</P>
<P>
The convention mapped out the future of boxing in general and
the sport in Africa in particular. According to the resolutions,
more African boxers and officials will have the opportunity to
participate in the WBC's championships.
</P>
<P>
An official of the South African Boxing Board, Peter Ngantane,
said the convention improved the networking and linking which
were very important for South Africans to get fights overseas.
</P>
<P>
He said the WBC also promised to bring more of its title
fights to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The WBC also inaugurated the building of a gymnasium in
Johannesburg, which was one of two gymnasiums the organization
had pledged to South Africa. The gymnasium will be named after
Muhammad Ali, one of the greatest boxers in history.  
</P>
</TEXT>
