<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor's Rule Enforced, Sindh Govt Stands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif announced Friday that the Governor's Rule has been
enforced in Sindh, the provincial government stands suspended and
action against terrorists has been started.
</P>
<P>
Sharif made the announcement in a televised address to the
nation Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the Governor's Rule, the Sindh Governor has been
directed to assume "all functions and powers of the province" on
behalf of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, the prime minister said that restoration of
peace and rule of law in the provincial capital of Karachi is the
main objective behind the decision.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has decided to uproot terrorism from the
country. The conspiracy to murder Hakim Said has been unearthed
and all those involved in the murder have been pointed out, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Hakim Said, former governor of Sindh and a prominent figure in
Pakistan, was killed in Karachi on October 17. The killing caused
shock among the general public.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that he had clearly told the Muttahida Qaumi
Movement (MQM) leaders who among their ranks were involved in this
murder and asked them to hand over the culprits.
</P>
<P>
So far the culprits have not been handed over to the
government, he said, adding the government cannot leave Karachi at
the mercy of criminals and terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Governor's Rule was being enforced in Sindh and
the provincial government stands dissolved, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif appealed to the nation particularly people in Karachi
and Sindh to fully cooperate with the government in its drive
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to politicians to play their due role of
providing peace and security to the people, keeping aside their
political differences.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Associated Press of Pakistan said Friday
evening that the Rabita Committee of the MQM has deplored the
enforcement of the Governor's Rule in Sindh.
</P>
<P>
The committee in a statement termed the move as
"anti-democratic".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats, Republicans Spar over Anti-Clinton Commercials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Battling for votes in next
Tuesday's mid-term elections, U.S. Vice President Al Gore and
Republicans exchanged bitter accusations.
</P>
<P>
Gore accused Speaker Newt Gingrich of the House of
Representatives of trying to turn the election into a personal
vendetta against President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Gore said he was "shocked" to learn from media reports that
Gingrich had personally devised and approved a 10 million-dollar
anti-Clinton Republican television advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
"The Republican attack machine has gone into overdrive, pouring
millions and millions of special interest dollars into negative
ads that personally attack the president," Gore said in a brief
appearance in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
Gore said, "These attacks personally devised by Speaker
Gingrich are wrong."
</P>
<P>
Shortly afterwards Republican Party chairman Jim Nicholson
called a news conference to respond to Gore's charges.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich spokeswoman Christina Martin said the ads were
accurate, "which is more than you can say for Al Gore."
</P>
<P>
"Newt Gingrich was aware but not involved in either the
scripting or the execution of these ads," she said. "In fact, Newt
Gingrich was no more a part of those ads than Al Gore was a part
of Bill Clinton's inappropriate behavior."
</P>
<P>
The November 3 vote will involve 34 senate seats, 36
governorships and all 435 seats in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Republicans, who have a big money advantage over Democrats,
launched a series of advertisements against Clinton in key
congressional districts earlier this week, arguing that Clinton
ought to be punished for lying to the American people about his
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
Democrats are expected to win the biggest single prize in the
elections -- the governorship of California. Democrat Gray Davis
led Republican Dan Lungren by 53 to 39 percent in the poll of
likely voters by the Field organization.
</P>
<P>
Republicans control 32 state governorships encompassing 75
percent of the U.S. population and have held California for the
past 16 years. They could add several more states this year,
including Florida, Maryland, Georgia and Colorado. But Democrats
are hoping to compensate by capturing Minnesota, Massachusetts,
Alabama and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
The election is likely to be interpreted as a referendum on
Clinton and on a Republican-led drive to impeach him on perjury
and obstruction of justice charges arising from the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
Polls have shown that more than two thirds of voters want the
Clinton scandal to be over and will not allow it to influence
their votes. But with turnout expected to be as low as 36 percent,
those who do care about the scandal could have a major impact on
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
Although the party holding the White House has lost an average
of 30 House seats in mid-term elections since 1930, its losses
have been much lower when the economy has been strong and the
president's job approval ratings have been high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
