<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Berger: China's Role to Profoundly Impact Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. National Security
Advisor Sandy Berger said here Friday that China plays an
important role in Asia and the world, and better ties with Beijing
will serve American interests.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the role China plays "will have a
profound impact on the new century" and that President Bill
Clinton's trip to China in June "advanced important American
interests."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's China trip was in return to a visit to the U.S. last
October by President Jiang Zemin of China. Both leaders agreed at
their Washington summit to establish "constructive strategic
partnership" between the two countries for the next century. Their
Beijing meeting was designed to maintain the momentum of improving
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"The president's trip to China in June advanced important
American interests, from seeking peace in Korea to reducing
weapons proliferation, to promoting cleaner technologies for our
environment," Berger said at a program sponsored by the National
Press Club.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States have agreed to cooperate on such
important issues like security, non-proliferation, drug
trafficking and international crimes, while still differing on
human rights, Taiwan and trade imbalance.
</P>
<P>
"Our strategy of engagement has brought results, though there
is still far to go," said Berger, who accompanied President
Clinton in his visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Despite reports on dissidents detention in China, the Asian
country "is becoming more open, not just to commerce but to ideas,
and our engagement is helping to empower the Chinese people as
they seek more freedom," the official said.
</P>
<P>
China signed the International Covenant on Civil and Political
Rights" early this month, and sponsored an international
conference on human rights in Beijing several weeks ago, pointing
to China's desire to settle the dispute with some Western
countries on the matter.
</P>
<P>
However, critics in the U.S. keep pressing the Administration
to change the course of improving relations with China, advocating
tougher policy toward China.
</P>
<P>
Berger defended the Administration's China engagement policy,
saying "a strategy of confrontation, by contrast, would likely
push China toward isolation, undermining our hopes for greater
democracy and stability in Asia."
</P>
<P>
"The policy of engagement that we have pursued over the past
three years has improved our relationship. There are still many
areas where we have serious differences with the Chinese, but we
confront those differences directly with them, face to face,"
Berger added.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the most serious difference between China
and the U.S. is on the Taiwan issue. During his visit to Shanghai
in late June, President Clinton announced "Three No's" on Taiwan
-- no support for Taiwan independence, no support for two Chinas
or one China one Taiwan, and no support for Taiwan's membership in
international organizations of sovereign states, but U.S. arms
sales to that island have never stopped.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has stepped up criticism recently of Washington for
selling more new advanced weapons to Taiwan and the study of
providing theater anti-missile defense systems to U.S. Asian
allies including Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Berger said that Washington would continue to seek better
relations with Beijing, while maintaining good informal ties with
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past 20 years we have had, generally, improving
relations with China. Our relationships with the people of Taiwan
have flourished. And this has been good for stability in the
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Berger rejected the accusation that better relations with China
were at the expense of ties with Taiwan, asserting "these things
do not have to come at the expense of one another."
</P>
<P>
He voiced strong support for cross-straits dialogue between
mainland China and Taiwan, calling such steps "constructive."
</P>
<P>
"This is a matter, obviously, for the peoples in China and
Taiwan to resolve themselves in a peaceful fashion. So we have
encouraged all involved to be forthcoming and constructive about
that dialogue," Berger said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
