<HEADLINE> Pastrana Outlines Policies on Drugs, Civil Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 30 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President Andres
Pastrana Friday outlined an interlocking strategy for ending the
civil conflict, curbing drug traffickers and revitalizing the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana, speaking at the National Press Club, said that
illicit drugs may one day disappear from Colombia. He was winding
up his state visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
A key breakthrough is the commitment of rebel leaders to help
eradicate drug crops if steps are taken to provide small farmers
with alternatives to narcotics plants, said Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
To help pay for the peace that he expects to begin negotiating
with the guerrillas, Pastrana said 100 million U.S. dollars has
been contributed by the Inter-American Development Bank, and that
a bond issue is expected to net nearly 800 million U.S. dollars
more.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the guerrillas and the international community
do not renege on their pledges of support, "we could eradicate
drugs from Colombia."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the fight against drug traffickers, Pastrana said,
"It is part of the fabric of my life." "I have been on the front
lines of this struggle. I am determined to win it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana expects to initiate peace talks next month with the
country's two largest guerrilla groups -- the Colombian
Revolutionary Armed Forces and the National Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
As a good-will gesture designed to build trust, he has agreed
to demilitarize a large section of rebel-held territory in
south-central Colombia for 90 days.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana sees that period as a test of the guerrillas'
willingness to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
Noting that poverty is the root cause of both the guerrilla war
and drug trafficking, Pastrana suggested that under conditions of
prosperity, young Colombians won't take up arms and farmers will
be content to cultivate legal crops instead of narcotics plants.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana began his visit to the U.S. Tuesday. It was the first
state visit by a Colombian president to the U.S. since 1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
