<DOCNO> XIE19981031.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council on Approaches to Comprehensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council on Friday sent a letter to U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, explaining its approaches to a comprehensive review of
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the Security Council reiterated its readiness to
consider, in the comprehensive review, Iraq's compliance with its
obligations under all relevant U.N. resolutions once Iraq resumes
its cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors and demonstrates that it
is prepared to fulfil all its obligation, including in particular
on disarmament issues.
</P>
<P>
The Council said it was ready to begin the comprehensive review
as soon as the U.N. chief confirms that the U.N. arms inspectors
are receiving full cooperation from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Council said It would begin the review by requesting
succinct reports for the Untied Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and
other relevant bodies, setting out Iraqi compliance with relevant
U.N. resolutions and identifying any tasks which still need to be
undertaken to satisfy the remaining requirements of the relevant
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
According to the letter, the Security Council would conduct the
review in two distinct phases. The first would assess Iraqi
compliance with its disarmament obligations under the relevant
resolutions, and would also include the arrangements for ongoing
monitoring and verification.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the review, which would follow immediately
after the first, on the basis likewise of succinct reports
prepared by the relevant bodies, would deal with Iraq's compliance
with all its other obligations under the relevant Security Council
resolutions, including those relating to Kuwaiti Prisoner of War
and Kuwaiti property.
</P>
<P>
The Council said Iraq should be invited to contribute its own
account of its compliance with its obligations, in the form of
written and oral presentation, with a clear explanation of its
reasoning.
</P>
<P>
Iraq wrote to the Security Council last Friday, asking when and
how the comprehensive review would be conducted. Iraq announced
to suspend cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors on August 5 after
talks between Iraq and UNSCOM collapsed.
</P>
<P>
As a response, the Security Council decided to suspend its
regular review of U.N. sanctions against Iraq until it resumes
cooperation. It, at the same, offered to conduct a comprehensive
review of Iraq's compliance with relevant U.N. resolutions, which
was initiated by the U.N. chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
